{"title_page": "Nico Mannion", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian-American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Nico Mannion\n| image = Nico Mannion.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Mannion in February 2020\n| number = 1\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lbs = 190\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = Arizona Wildcats\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|3|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Siena]], Italy\n| nationality = Italian / American\n| high_school = [[Pinnacle High School|Pinnacle]]<br>([[Phoenix, Arizona]])\n| college = [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] (2019\u20132020)\n| highlights = \n* Second-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] ([[2019\u201320 Pac-12 Conference men's basketball season|2020]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2019 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2019]])\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2019)\n| medal_templates = \n}}\n'''Niccol\u00f2 \"Nico\" Mannion''' (born March 14, 2001) is an Italian-American [[college basketball]] player for the [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona Wildcats]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. He previously played for [[Pinnacle High School]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], where he was a five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] and one of the top [[point guard]]s in the 2019 recruiting class. Although he mainly grew up in the United States, Mannion represents his birth country of [[Italy national basketball team|Italy]] in international competitions.\n\n==Early life==\nNico was born in [[Siena]], Italy, where he spent his early childhood before his family moved to [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], and finally settled in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=\"holmes\">{{cite web |last1=Holmes |first1=C. J. |title=The Pace Mannion Influence: How Nico draws strength and wisdom from Dad |url=https://theathletic.com/1537502/2020/01/16/the-pace-mannion-influence-how-nico-draws-strength-and-wisdom-from-dad/ |website=[[The Athletic]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nAs a freshman, Mannion began playing basketball for [[Pinnacle High School]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]] under head coach Charlie Wilde.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recruiting Update: Nico Mannion (2020) |url=https://www.prephoops.com/2016/06/recruiting-update-nico-mannion-2020/ |publisher=PrepHoops |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> On February 9, 2017, he featured in a ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' article, \"A 15-Year-Old (Sorta-Maybe) Basketball Prodigy\".<ref name=\"Ballard\">{{cite web |last1=Ballard |first1=Chris |title=A 15-Year-Old (Sorta-Maybe) Basketball Prodigy |url=https://www.si.com/longform/2017/nico-mannion-high-school-basketball/index.html |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=February 9, 2017}}</ref> Mannion started in all 28 of his games, averaging 20.2 points, 4.6 rebounds, 4.7 assists, and 2.4 steals per game while leading Pinnacle to a 22\u20136 record.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion |url=https://www.usab.com/basketball/players/mens/m/mannion-nico.aspx |publisher=[[USA Basketball]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> He was named [[MaxPreps]] first team All-American and ''[[The Arizona Republic|Arizona Republic]]'' Class 6A first team All-State.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016-17 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Freshman All-American Team |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/EVB78NqOWEaYDifF0xyXpg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-freshman-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Entering his sophomore season, Mannion was named to the ''[[USA Today]]'' All-USA Arizona preseason team. He missed his first four games with a broken left hand.<ref name=\"Midseason\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Top 50 Arizona high school boys basketball players mid-season rankings |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2017/11/22/top-50-arizona-high-school-boys-basketball-players-2017-18-season/863054001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=November 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=American Family Insurance ALL-USA Arizona preseason boys basketball team 2017-18 |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/all-usa/2017/11/21/american-family-insurance-all-usa-arizona-preseason-boys-basketball-team-2017-18/887161001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> On February 28, 2018, Mannion scored 21 points in a 76\u201360 win over [[Mountain Pointe High School]] for the Class 6A state championship.<ref name=\"MountainPointe\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Pinnacle boys basketball dominates Mountain Pointe for 6A title |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/02/28/pinnacle-boys-basketball-dominates-mountain-pointe-6-title/383985002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=February 28, 2018}}</ref> He finished the season averaging 23.4 points, 4.7 rebounds, and 5.8 assists per game, leading Pinnacle to a 24\u20137 record.<ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=2017-18 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Sophomore All-American Team |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/yL1wLxRGiUeRCLlOOrsePA/2017-18-maxpreps-boys-basketball-sophomore-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> Mannion received MaxPreps Sophomore All-American third team and Arizona [[Gatorade Player of the Year awards|Gatorade Player of the Year]] distinction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion 2017 - 2018 Arizona Boys Basketball Player of the Year |url=https://playeroftheyear.gatorade.com/winner/nico-mannion/36417 |publisher=[[Gatorade]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe took online summer courses to be able to graduate in the following spring.<ref name=\"Reclass\">{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Jenna |title=Five-Star Recruit Nico Mannion Reclassifies From 2020 to 2019 Class |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/07/20/nico-mannion-reclassify-2019-class-five-star-recruit |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> On December 1, Mannion scored 37 points, including the game-winning three-pointer, in an 82\u201380 victory over [[Shadow Mountain High School]], who had won 73 straight games against Arizona opponents.<ref name=\"ShadowMountain\">{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle knock off No. 13 Shadow Mountain to snap 73-game Arizona win streak |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/x5DYRWwP_kmpPkaD-Cq1Eg/nico-mannion,-pinnacle-knock-off-no-13-shadow-mountain-to-snap-73-game-arizona-win-streak.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ShadowMountain2\">{{cite web |title=Mannion's buzzer-beater lifts Pinnacle past Shadow Mountain |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/11/30/shadow-mountain-pinnacle-boys-basketball/2165597002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> MaxPreps writer Jordan Divens said that Mannion's performance in the game \"will go down in Arizona high school basketball lore.\"<ref name=ShadowMountain/> Five days later, Mannion recorded 33 points and 12 assists in a nationally televised game against top recruit [[Jalen Green]] and [[San Joaquin Memorial High School]] at the Hoophall West Invitational.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Nico Mannion puts on a show against top-rated Jalen Green in Pinnacle rout |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/12/06/pinnacles-nico-mannion-puts-show-against-top-rated-jalen-green/2221224002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 30, he scored 45 points in an 88\u201378 loss to [[Mater Dei High School (Santa Ana, California)|Mater Dei High School]] at the Rancho Mirage Holiday Invitational National Division championship.<ref name=\"MaterDei\">{{cite web |last1=John |first1=Andrew L. |title=Mater Dei overcomes Nico Mannion's 45 points to win Rancho Mirage Invitational title |url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/sports/basketball/2018/12/30/mater-dei-overcomes-nico-mannions-45-points-win-rancho-mirage-title/2444525002/ |website=[[The Desert Sun]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Mannion, on February 2, 2019, tallied 57 points, including the game-winning shot as time expired, to help defeat [[Chaparral High School (Arizona)|Chaparral High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=Arizona Wildcats signee Nico Mannion scores 57 in high school senior night game |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/pascoe/arizona-wildcats-signee-nico-mannion-scores-in-high-school-senior/article_3d39d270-26a8-11e9-88f7-df0f3e133788.html |website=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=February 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 27, he led Pinnacle to a second Class 6A state title, posting 34 points, eight rebounds, and six assists in an 83\u201364 win over Chaparral High School.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelapire |first1=Ryan |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle capture second straight 6A state championship |url=https://www.azdesertswarm.com/basketball/2019/2/26/18242542/nico-mannion-pinnacle-state-championship-chaparral-highlights-arizona-basketball-recruiting-2019 |publisher=Arizona Desert Swarm |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> By the end of the season, Mannion was averaging 30.4 points, 6.2 rebounds, and 6.2 assists per game.<ref name=\"NHSCA\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Pinnacle's Nico Mannion receives national basketball honor |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2019/04/08/arizona-bound-nico-mannion-named-national-seniors-hs-basketball-poy/3405334002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> He reclaimed the Arizona Gatorade Player of the Year award and was recognized as National High School Coaches Association (NHSCA) Senior Athlete of the Year.<ref name=\"Potter\">{{cite web |last1=Potter |first1=Mattie |title=Arizona's Mannion named 2018-2019 Boys' Basketball Athlete of the Year |url=https://www.nhsca.com/news/445693/info@nhsca.com |publisher=National High School Coaches Association |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=David |title=Nico Mannion repeats as Gatorade Arizona Boys Basketball Player of the Year |url=https://zonazealots.com/2019/03/15/nico-mannion-repeats-gatorade-arizona-boys-basketball-playeryear/ |publisher=Zona Zealots |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> Mannion also earned ''USA Today'' All-USA second team and [[Naismith Prep Player of the Year Award|Naismith]] All-American third team honors.<ref name=NHSCA/><ref>{{cite web |title=2018-19 ALL-USA High School Boys Basketball: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2019/2018-19-all-usa-high-school-boys-basketball-second-team |publisher=USA Today High School Sports |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 2, 2019}}</ref> In the spring, he played in the [[2019 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|McDonald's All-American Game]] and [[Nike Hoop Summit]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelapire |first1=Ryan |title=Josh Green, Nico Mannion score 8 points apiece in McDonald\u2019s All-American Game |url=https://www.azdesertswarm.com/basketball/2019/3/27/18284770/josh-green-nico-mannion-mcdonalds-all-american-game-stats-highlights-box-score-arizona-wildcats |publisher=Arizona Desert Swarm |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=People react to Arizona Wildcats-bound Nico Mannion putting on a show at Nike Hoop Summit |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2019/people-react-to-arizona-wildcats-bound-nico-mannion-putting-on-a-show-at-nike-hoops-summit |publisher=USA Today High School SPorts |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Recruiting===\nMannion was considered the top player in the 2020 recruiting class by [[Scout.com]], [[Rivals.com]] and [[ESPN]]. But he reclassified to the 2019 class. Mannion received his first [[college basketball]] offer from [[Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball|Cal State Northridge]] while in eighth grade.<ref name=\"Bossi\">{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |title=Sharp shooting 2020 PG Nico Mannion holds several offers |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/usa-bball-sharp-shooting-2020-pg-nico-mannion-holds-several-offers |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> In high school, he picked up offers from several major [[NCAA Division I]] programs, including [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] and [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]].<ref name=\"ESPNr\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/226820/nico-mannion |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> Mannion was a consensus five-star recruit and the best recruit from Arizona in the 2019 class.<ref name=\"247Sports\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle, Point Guard |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Nico-Mannion-46035982/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Rivals\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion, 2019 Point guard |url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/2019/nico-mannion-181233 |publisher=[[Rivals.com]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> On September 14, 2018, he committed to [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] over [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]].<ref name=\"Commit\">{{cite web |last1=Biancardi |first1=Paul |title=No. 2 PG recruit Nico Mannion chooses Arizona over Marquette |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/24677774/no-2-pg-recruit-nico-mannion-chooses-arizona-marquette |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2019}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Nico Mannion\n| position = [[Point guard|PG]]\n| hometown = [[Siena|Siena, Italy]]\n| highschool = [[Pinnacle High School|Pinnacle]] (AZ)\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 3\n| weight = 180\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = September 14, 2018 \n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars = 5\n| espn stars = 5\n| espn grade = 96\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit End\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2019\n| rivals ref title = Arizona 2019 Basketball Commitments\n| espn ref title   = 2019 Arizona Wildcats Recruiting Class\n| rivals school    = arizona\n| espn schoolid    = 12\n| 247 overall      = 8\n| rivals overall   = 14\n| espn overall     = 9\n| accessdate       = April 5, 2019\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n==College career==\nMannion earned preseason first-team All-[[Pac-12 Conference]] honors and was named to the preseason watch lists for the [[John R. Wooden Award|Wooden Award]] and [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pac-12 unveils inaugural men's basketball preseason All-Conference teams |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2019/10/08/pac-12-unveils-inaugural-mens-basketball-preseason-all-conference-teams |publisher=[[Pac-12 Conference]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> In his second collegiate game for [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]], on November 6, 2019, he recorded 23 points, nine assists and four rebounds in a 90\u201369 win over [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=Freshmen Nico Mannion, Josh Green lead Arizona past Illinois |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/college/ua/2019/11/10/freshmen-nico-mannion-josh-green-lead-arizona-past-illinois/2559940001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> On November 28, Mannion posted 16 points and 11 assists and made a game-winning [[layup]] with four seconds left in a 93\u201391 victory over [[Pepperdine Waves men's basketball|Pepperdine]] in the first round of the [[Wooden Legacy]].<ref name=\"pepperdine\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion\u2019s last-second layup saves No. 14 Arizona against Pepperdine |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nico-mannion-last-second-layup-152343254.html |website=[[Yahoo Sports]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=November 29, 2019}}</ref> In a second round win over [[Penn Quakers men's basketball|Penn]], he scored a season-high 24 points. Mannion led his team to the Wooden Legacy title and was named tournament [[most valuable player]] (MVP) after averaging 16.3 points and 7.3 assists per game. In the following day, he earned Pac-12 freshman of the week accolades.<ref name=\"fotw\">{{cite web |title=Martin, Mannion collect Pac-12 Men's Basketball weekly honors |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2019/12/02/martin-mannion-collect-pac-12-mens-basketball-weekly-honors |publisher=[[Pac-12 Conference]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=December 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 29, 2020, Mannion had 19 points and six assists in a 69\u201364 loss to [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=On Sean Miller's 'conversations' with officials at UCLA, Josh Green's absence and silver linings |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/pascoe/on-sean-miller-s-conversations-with-officials-at-ucla-josh/article_ccff0fe8-5b8f-11ea-84c5-e32b03bfe40c.html |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |work=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> At the conclusion of the regular season, Mannion was named to the [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] second team and the All-Freshman Team.<ref name=\"Pac-12 Awards\">{{Cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/article/2020/03/08/2019-20-pac-12-mens-basketball-all-conference-awards-announced|title=Pac-12 announces 2019-20 Men's Basketball annual major awards|date=March 9, 2020|website=pac-12.com|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Mannion averaged 14.0 points and 5.3 assists per game as a freshman. Following the season, he declared for the [[2020 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Keith |title=Arizona\u2019s Nico Mannion to declare for 2020 NBA Draft |url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/08/nico-mannion-nba-draft/ |work=[[NBC Sports]] |date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nMannion holds [[Multiple citizenship|dual citizenship]] to the United States and Italy; his father is American, while his mother is Italian.<ref name=USA/><ref name=\"Costa\">{{cite web |last1=Costa |first1=Dario |title=Born ready - The Story of Nico Mannion |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/fiba/news/born-ready-the-story-of-nico-mannion/14hjnocdnv5nx1bl6a87jzjj2q |website=[[Sporting News]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 14, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, he joined training camp with the [[United States men's national under-17 basketball team|United States national under-16 team]] and was a finalist for its [[2017 FIBA Under-16 Americas Championship]] roster.<ref name=USA/><ref name=\"Snub\">{{cite web |title=Not making USA team gives Mannion shot at U17 Basketball World Cup with Italy |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u16/2017/news/not-making-usa-team-gives-mannion-shot-at-u17-basketball-world-cup-with-italy |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> After not making the team, he was contacted by the [[Italian Basketball Federation]] and joined the [[Italy men's national under-16 basketball team|Italian national under-16 team]] at the [[2017 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] in [[Podgorica]], Montenegro.<ref name=Snub/><ref name=\"Qualifiers\">{{cite web |title=Italian teen phenom Nico Mannion leaves lasting impression on senior national team debut in World Cup Qualifiers |url=https://www.fiba.basketball/basketballworldcup/2019/european-qualifiers/news/italian-teen-phenom-nico-mannion-leaves-lasting-impression-on-senior-national-team-debut-in-world-cup-qualifiers |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=July 4, 2018}}</ref> Mannion made his debut on August 11, 2017, recording 15 points and seven assists in a 64\u201359 loss to [[France national under-17 basketball team|France]].<ref name=\"Gershon\">{{cite web |last1=Gershon |first1=Josh |title=FIBA u16 A: Four-star PG Nico Mannion impresses with Italy |url=https://www.scout.com/Article/FIBA-u16-A-Four-star-2020-PG-Nico-Mannion-impresses-with-Italy-in-international-debut-106044334/ |publisher=[[Scout.com]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> Two days later, he posted 42 points, five rebounds, and six steals in 29 minutes in an 86\u201357 victory over [[Russia national under-17 basketball team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Manion scored 42 points in 29 minutes |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/fiba/495450/manion-scored-42-points-29-minutes/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> Through seven games, Mannion averaged a tournament-high 19.9 points, 5.7 rebounds, 4.0 assists, and 3.0 steals per game, leading Italy to a ninth-place finish.<ref name=\"RealGM\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion Player Profile |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Nico-Mannion/Summary/117373 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Obert\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Nico Mannion narrows college choices to Arizona, Marquette |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/recruiting/2017/08/28/recruiting-pinnacle-point-guard-nico-mannion/608545001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe debuted for the senior [[Italy national basketball team|Italian national team]] at [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup qualification (Europe)|European qualifiers]] for the [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019 FIBA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Pascoe\">{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=He just wants to win: Future Wildcat Nico Mannion doesn't let anything get in his way |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/he-just-wants-to-win-future-wildcat-nico-mannion-doesn/article_93bb05cf-ada5-5260-ae6d-b124838bd23c.html |website=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> In his sole appearance on July 1, 2018, Mannion scored nine points in 29 minutes in an 81\u201366 loss to the [[Netherlands national basketball team|Netherlands]], becoming the fourth-youngest player in team history at age 17.<ref name=Qualifiers/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 Arizona Wildcats men's basketball team|Arizona]]\n| 32 || 32 || 32.3 || .392 || .327 || .797 || 2.5 || 5.3 || 1.2 || .0 || 14.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMannion is the son of an American father and an Italian mother. His father, [[Pace Mannion]], is a former [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player who played for six different NBA teams through the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pace Mannion Stats |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mannipa01.html |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He played professionally for various teams in Italy until his retirement in 2002.<ref name=\"Melloni\">{{cite web |last1=Melloni |first1=Mirco |title=L\u2019Italia ha il suo Mamba: la storia di Nico Mannion, fenomeno delle giovanili azzurre |url=https://www.lastampa.it/2017/08/14/sport/litalia-ha-il-suo-mamba-la-storia-di-nico-mannion-fenomeno-delle-giovanili-azzurre-fA4EOLFEezmgTsLco7Wz3L/pagina.html |website=[[La Stampa]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |language=Italian |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frangipani |first1=Niccol\u00f2 |title=Astri Nascenti nel Basket: Nico Mannion, the italian stallion |url=http://www.vita-sportiva.it/2018/08/11/nico-mannion-the-italian-stallion/ |publisher=Vita Sportiva |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Most notably, he helped Italian club [[Pallacanestro Cant\u00f9]] win the [[1990\u201391 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|1991 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]].<ref name=Snub/> Mannion's mother, Gaia Bianchi, is a former [[volleyball]] player who played for the [[Italy women's national volleyball team|Italian national volleyball team]].<ref name=\"Boivin\">{{cite web |last1=Boivin |first1=Paola |title=Boivin: Pinnacle freshman Nico Mannion creating national buzz |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2016/12/14/boivin-pinnacle-prodigy-mannion-creating-buzz-nice-pace-basketball/95442212/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://arizonawildcats.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/nico-mannion/10611 Arizona Wildcats bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mannion, Nico}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Italian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Italian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Siena]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian-American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Nico Mannion\n| image = Nico Mannion.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Mannion in February 2020\n| number = 1\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lbs = 190\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = Arizona Wildcats\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|3|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Siena]], Italy\n| nationality = Italian / American\n| high_school = [[Pinnacle High School|Pinnacle]]<br>([[Phoenix, Arizona]])\n| college = [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] (2019\u20132020)\n| highlights = \n* Second-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] ([[2019\u201320 Pac-12 Conference men's basketball season|2020]])\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2019 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2019]])\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2019)\n| medal_templates = \n}}\n'''Niccol\u00f2 \"Nico\" Mannion''' (born March 14, 2001) is an Italian-American [[college basketball]] player for the [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona Wildcats]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. He previously played for [[Pinnacle High School]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], where he was a five-star [[college recruiting|recruit]] and one of the top [[point guard]]s in the 2019 recruiting class. Although he mainly grew up in the United States, Mannion represents his birth country of [[Italy national basketball team|Italy]] in international competitions.\n\n==Early life==\nNico was born in [[Siena]], Italy, where he spent his early childhood before his family moved to [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], and finally settled in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref name=\"holmes\">{{cite web |last1=Holmes |first1=C. J. |title=The Pace Mannion Influence: How Nico draws strength and wisdom from Dad |url=https://theathletic.com/1537502/2020/01/16/the-pace-mannion-influence-how-nico-draws-strength-and-wisdom-from-dad/ |website=[[The Athletic]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nAs a freshman, Mannion began playing basketball for [[Pinnacle High School]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]] under head coach Charlie Wilde.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recruiting Update: Nico Mannion (2020) |url=https://www.prephoops.com/2016/06/recruiting-update-nico-mannion-2020/ |publisher=PrepHoops |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> On February 9, 2017, he featured in a ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' article, \"A 15-Year-Old (Sorta-Maybe) Basketball Prodigy\".<ref name=\"Ballard\">{{cite web |last1=Ballard |first1=Chris |title=A 15-Year-Old (Sorta-Maybe) Basketball Prodigy |url=https://www.si.com/longform/2017/nico-mannion-high-school-basketball/index.html |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=February 9, 2017}}</ref> Mannion started in all 28 of his games, averaging 20.2 points, 4.6 rebounds, 4.7 assists, and 2.4 steals per game while leading Pinnacle to a 22\u20136 record.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion |url=https://www.usab.com/basketball/players/mens/m/mannion-nico.aspx |publisher=[[USA Basketball]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> He was named [[MaxPreps]] first team All-American and ''[[The Arizona Republic|Arizona Republic]]'' Class 6A first team All-State.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016-17 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Freshman All-American Team |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/EVB78NqOWEaYDifF0xyXpg/2016-17-maxpreps-boys-basketball-freshman-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> Entering his sophomore season, Mannion was named to the ''[[USA Today]]'' All-USA Arizona preseason team. He missed his first four games with a broken left hand.<ref name=\"Midseason\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Top 50 Arizona high school boys basketball players mid-season rankings |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2017/11/22/top-50-arizona-high-school-boys-basketball-players-2017-18-season/863054001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=November 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=American Family Insurance ALL-USA Arizona preseason boys basketball team 2017-18 |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/all-usa/2017/11/21/american-family-insurance-all-usa-arizona-preseason-boys-basketball-team-2017-18/887161001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> On February 28, 2018, Mannion scored 21 points in a 76\u201360 win over [[Mountain Pointe High School]] for the Class 6A state championship.<ref name=\"MountainPointe\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Pinnacle boys basketball dominates Mountain Pointe for 6A title |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/02/28/pinnacle-boys-basketball-dominates-mountain-pointe-6-title/383985002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=February 28, 2018}}</ref> He finished the season averaging 23.4 points, 4.7 rebounds, and 5.8 assists per game, leading Pinnacle to a 24\u20137 record.<ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=2017-18 MaxPreps Boys Basketball Sophomore All-American Team |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/yL1wLxRGiUeRCLlOOrsePA/2017-18-maxpreps-boys-basketball-sophomore-all-american-team.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> Mannion received MaxPreps Sophomore All-American third team and Arizona [[Gatorade Player of the Year awards|Gatorade Player of the Year]] distinction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion 2017 - 2018 Arizona Boys Basketball Player of the Year |url=https://playeroftheyear.gatorade.com/winner/nico-mannion/36417 |publisher=[[Gatorade]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe took online summer courses to be able to graduate in the following spring.<ref name=\"Reclass\">{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Jenna |title=Five-Star Recruit Nico Mannion Reclassifies From 2020 to 2019 Class |url=https://www.si.com/college-basketball/2018/07/20/nico-mannion-reclassify-2019-class-five-star-recruit |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> On December 1, Mannion scored 37 points, including the game-winning three-pointer, in an 82\u201380 victory over [[Shadow Mountain High School]], who had won 73 straight games against Arizona opponents.<ref name=\"ShadowMountain\">{{cite web |last1=Divens |first1=Jordan |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle knock off No. 13 Shadow Mountain to snap 73-game Arizona win streak |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/x5DYRWwP_kmpPkaD-Cq1Eg/nico-mannion,-pinnacle-knock-off-no-13-shadow-mountain-to-snap-73-game-arizona-win-streak.htm |publisher=[[MaxPreps]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ShadowMountain2\">{{cite web |title=Mannion's buzzer-beater lifts Pinnacle past Shadow Mountain |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/11/30/shadow-mountain-pinnacle-boys-basketball/2165597002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> MaxPreps writer Jordan Divens said that Mannion's performance in the game \"will go down in Arizona high school basketball lore.\"<ref name=ShadowMountain/> Five days later, Mannion recorded 33 points and 12 assists in a nationally televised game against top recruit [[Jalen Green]] and [[San Joaquin Memorial High School]] at the Hoophall West Invitational.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Nico Mannion puts on a show against top-rated Jalen Green in Pinnacle rout |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2018/12/06/pinnacles-nico-mannion-puts-show-against-top-rated-jalen-green/2221224002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 30, he scored 45 points in an 88\u201378 loss to [[Mater Dei High School (Santa Ana, California)|Mater Dei High School]] at the Rancho Mirage Holiday Invitational National Division championship.<ref name=\"MaterDei\">{{cite web |last1=John |first1=Andrew L. |title=Mater Dei overcomes Nico Mannion's 45 points to win Rancho Mirage Invitational title |url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/sports/basketball/2018/12/30/mater-dei-overcomes-nico-mannions-45-points-win-rancho-mirage-title/2444525002/ |website=[[The Desert Sun]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Mannion, on February 2, 2019, tallied 57 points, including the game-winning shot as time expired, to help defeat [[Chaparral High School (Arizona)|Chaparral High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=Arizona Wildcats signee Nico Mannion scores 57 in high school senior night game |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/pascoe/arizona-wildcats-signee-nico-mannion-scores-in-high-school-senior/article_3d39d270-26a8-11e9-88f7-df0f3e133788.html |website=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=February 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 27, he led Pinnacle to a second Class 6A state title, posting 34 points, eight rebounds, and six assists in an 83\u201364 win over Chaparral High School.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelapire |first1=Ryan |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle capture second straight 6A state championship |url=https://www.azdesertswarm.com/basketball/2019/2/26/18242542/nico-mannion-pinnacle-state-championship-chaparral-highlights-arizona-basketball-recruiting-2019 |publisher=Arizona Desert Swarm |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=February 26, 2019}}</ref> By the end of the season, Mannion was averaging 30.4 points, 6.2 rebounds, and 6.2 assists per game.<ref name=\"NHSCA\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Pinnacle's Nico Mannion receives national basketball honor |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2019/04/08/arizona-bound-nico-mannion-named-national-seniors-hs-basketball-poy/3405334002/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> He reclaimed the Arizona Gatorade Player of the Year award and was recognized as National High School Coaches Association (NHSCA) Senior Athlete of the Year.<ref name=\"Potter\">{{cite web |last1=Potter |first1=Mattie |title=Arizona's Mannion named 2018-2019 Boys' Basketball Athlete of the Year |url=https://www.nhsca.com/news/445693/info@nhsca.com |publisher=National High School Coaches Association |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=David |title=Nico Mannion repeats as Gatorade Arizona Boys Basketball Player of the Year |url=https://zonazealots.com/2019/03/15/nico-mannion-repeats-gatorade-arizona-boys-basketball-playeryear/ |publisher=Zona Zealots |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> Mannion also earned ''USA Today'' All-USA second team and [[Naismith Prep Player of the Year Award|Naismith]] All-American third team honors.<ref name=NHSCA/><ref>{{cite web |title=2018-19 ALL-USA High School Boys Basketball: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2019/2018-19-all-usa-high-school-boys-basketball-second-team |publisher=USA Today High School Sports |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 2, 2019}}</ref> In the spring, he played in the [[2019 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|McDonald's All-American Game]] and [[Nike Hoop Summit]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelapire |first1=Ryan |title=Josh Green, Nico Mannion score 8 points apiece in McDonald\u2019s All-American Game |url=https://www.azdesertswarm.com/basketball/2019/3/27/18284770/josh-green-nico-mannion-mcdonalds-all-american-game-stats-highlights-box-score-arizona-wildcats |publisher=Arizona Desert Swarm |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=People react to Arizona Wildcats-bound Nico Mannion putting on a show at Nike Hoop Summit |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2019/people-react-to-arizona-wildcats-bound-nico-mannion-putting-on-a-show-at-nike-hoops-summit |publisher=USA Today High School SPorts |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |date=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Recruiting===\nMannion was considered the top player in the 2020 recruiting class by [[Scout.com]], [[Rivals.com]] and [[ESPN]]. But he reclassified to the 2019 class. Mannion received his first [[college basketball]] offer from [[Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball|Cal State Northridge]] while in eighth grade.<ref name=\"Bossi\">{{cite web |last1=Bossi |first1=Eric |title=Sharp shooting 2020 PG Nico Mannion holds several offers |url=https://basketballrecruiting.rivals.com/news/usa-bball-sharp-shooting-2020-pg-nico-mannion-holds-several-offers |publisher=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> In high school, he picked up offers from several major [[NCAA Division I]] programs, including [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] and [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]].<ref name=\"ESPNr\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/226820/nico-mannion |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> Mannion was a consensus five-star recruit and the best recruit from Arizona in the 2019 class.<ref name=\"247Sports\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion, Pinnacle, Point Guard |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Nico-Mannion-46035982/ |publisher=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Rivals\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion, 2019 Point guard |url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/2019/nico-mannion-181233 |publisher=[[Rivals.com]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> On September 14, 2018, he committed to [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] over [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]].<ref name=\"Commit\">{{cite web |last1=Biancardi |first1=Paul |title=No. 2 PG recruit Nico Mannion chooses Arizona over Marquette |url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/24677774/no-2-pg-recruit-nico-mannion-chooses-arizona-marquette |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2019}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Nico Mannion\n| position = [[Point guard|PG]]\n| hometown = [[Siena|Siena, Italy]]\n| highschool = [[Pinnacle High School|Pinnacle]] (AZ)\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 3\n| weight = 180\n| 40     =\n| commitdate = September 14, 2018 \n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars = 5\n| espn stars = 5\n| espn grade = 96\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit End\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2019\n| rivals ref title = Arizona 2019 Basketball Commitments\n| espn ref title   = 2019 Arizona Wildcats Recruiting Class\n| rivals school    = arizona\n| espn schoolid    = 12\n| 247 overall      = 8\n| rivals overall   = 14\n| espn overall     = 9\n| accessdate       = April 5, 2019\n| bball            = yes\n}}\n\n==College career==\nMannion earned preseason first-team All-[[Pac-12 Conference]] honors and was named to the preseason watch lists for the [[John R. Wooden Award|Wooden Award]] and [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pac-12 unveils inaugural men's basketball preseason All-Conference teams |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2019/10/08/pac-12-unveils-inaugural-mens-basketball-preseason-all-conference-teams |publisher=[[Pac-12 Conference]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> In his second collegiate game for [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]], on November 6, 2019, he recorded 23 points, nine assists and four rebounds in a 90\u201369 win over [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=Freshmen Nico Mannion, Josh Green lead Arizona past Illinois |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/college/ua/2019/11/10/freshmen-nico-mannion-josh-green-lead-arizona-past-illinois/2559940001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> On November 28, Mannion posted 16 points and 11 assists and made a game-winning [[layup]] with four seconds left in a 93\u201391 victory over [[Pepperdine Waves men's basketball|Pepperdine]] in the first round of the [[Wooden Legacy]].<ref name=\"pepperdine\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion\u2019s last-second layup saves No. 14 Arizona against Pepperdine |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nico-mannion-last-second-layup-152343254.html |website=[[Yahoo Sports]] |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=November 29, 2019}}</ref> In a second round win over [[Penn Quakers men's basketball|Penn]], he scored a season-high 24 points. Mannion led his team to the Wooden Legacy title and was named tournament [[most valuable player]] (MVP) after averaging 16.3 points and 7.3 assists per game. In the following day, he earned Pac-12 freshman of the week accolades.<ref name=\"fotw\">{{cite web |title=Martin, Mannion collect Pac-12 Men's Basketball weekly honors |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2019/12/02/martin-mannion-collect-pac-12-mens-basketball-weekly-honors |publisher=[[Pac-12 Conference]] |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |date=December 2, 2019}}</ref> On February 29, 2020, Mannion had 19 points and six assists in a 69\u201364 loss to [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=On Sean Miller's 'conversations' with officials at UCLA, Josh Green's absence and silver linings |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/pascoe/on-sean-miller-s-conversations-with-officials-at-ucla-josh/article_ccff0fe8-5b8f-11ea-84c5-e32b03bfe40c.html |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |work=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> At the conclusion of the regular season, Mannion was named to the [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] second team and the All-Freshman Team.<ref name=\"Pac-12 Awards\">{{Cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/article/2020/03/08/2019-20-pac-12-mens-basketball-all-conference-awards-announced|title=Pac-12 announces 2019-20 Men's Basketball annual major awards|date=March 9, 2020|website=pac-12.com|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Mannion averaged 14.0 points and 5.3 assists per game as a freshman. Following the season, he declared for the [[2020 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Keith |title=Arizona\u2019s Nico Mannion to declare for 2020 NBA Draft |url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/08/nico-mannion-nba-draft/ |work=[[NBC Sports]] |date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nMannion holds [[Multiple citizenship|dual citizenship]] to the United States and Italy; his father is American, while his mother is Italian.<ref name=USA/><ref name=\"Costa\">{{cite web |last1=Costa |first1=Dario |title=Born ready - The Story of Nico Mannion |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/fiba/news/born-ready-the-story-of-nico-mannion/14hjnocdnv5nx1bl6a87jzjj2q |website=[[Sporting News]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 14, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, he joined training camp with the [[United States men's national under-17 basketball team|United States national under-16 team]] and was a finalist for its [[2017 FIBA Under-16 Americas Championship]] roster.<ref name=USA/><ref name=\"Snub\">{{cite web |title=Not making USA team gives Mannion shot at U17 Basketball World Cup with Italy |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u16/2017/news/not-making-usa-team-gives-mannion-shot-at-u17-basketball-world-cup-with-italy |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> After not making the team, he was contacted by the [[Italian Basketball Federation]] and joined the [[Italy men's national under-16 basketball team|Italian national under-16 team]] at the [[2017 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] in [[Podgorica]], Montenegro.<ref name=Snub/><ref name=\"Qualifiers\">{{cite web |title=Italian teen phenom Nico Mannion leaves lasting impression on senior national team debut in World Cup Qualifiers |url=https://www.fiba.basketball/basketballworldcup/2019/european-qualifiers/news/italian-teen-phenom-nico-mannion-leaves-lasting-impression-on-senior-national-team-debut-in-world-cup-qualifiers |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=July 4, 2018}}</ref> Mannion made his debut on August 11, 2017, recording 15 points and seven assists in a 64\u201359 loss to [[France national under-17 basketball team|France]].<ref name=\"Gershon\">{{cite web |last1=Gershon |first1=Josh |title=FIBA u16 A: Four-star PG Nico Mannion impresses with Italy |url=https://www.scout.com/Article/FIBA-u16-A-Four-star-2020-PG-Nico-Mannion-impresses-with-Italy-in-international-debut-106044334/ |publisher=[[Scout.com]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> Two days later, he posted 42 points, five rebounds, and six steals in 29 minutes in an 86\u201357 victory over [[Russia national under-17 basketball team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Manion scored 42 points in 29 minutes |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/fiba/495450/manion-scored-42-points-29-minutes/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> Through seven games, Mannion averaged a tournament-high 19.9 points, 5.7 rebounds, 4.0 assists, and 3.0 steals per game, leading Italy to a ninth-place finish.<ref name=\"RealGM\">{{cite web |title=Nico Mannion Player Profile |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Nico-Mannion/Summary/117373 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Obert\">{{cite web |last1=Obert |first1=Richard |title=Nico Mannion narrows college choices to Arizona, Marquette |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/recruiting/2017/08/28/recruiting-pinnacle-point-guard-nico-mannion/608545001/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe debuted for the senior [[Italy national basketball team|Italian national team]] at [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup qualification (Europe)|European qualifiers]] for the [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019 FIBA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Pascoe\">{{cite web |last1=Pascoe |first1=Bruce |title=He just wants to win: Future Wildcat Nico Mannion doesn't let anything get in his way |url=https://tucson.com/sports/arizonawildcats/basketball/he-just-wants-to-win-future-wildcat-nico-mannion-doesn/article_93bb05cf-ada5-5260-ae6d-b124838bd23c.html |website=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019 |date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> In his sole appearance on July 1, 2018, Mannion scored nine points in 29 minutes in an 81\u201366 loss to the [[Netherlands national basketball team|Netherlands]], becoming the fourth-youngest player in team history at age 17.<ref name=Qualifiers/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 Arizona Wildcats men's basketball team|Arizona]]\n| 32 || 32 || 32.3 || .392 || .327 || .797 || 2.5 || 5.3 || 1.2 || .0 || 14.0\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMannion is the son of an American father and Italian mother. His father, [[Pace Mannion]], is a former [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player who played for six different NBA teams through the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pace Mannion Stats |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/mannipa01.html |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He played professionally for various teams in Italy until his retirement in 2002.<ref name=\"Melloni\">{{cite web |last1=Melloni |first1=Mirco |title=L\u2019Italia ha il suo Mamba: la storia di Nico Mannion, fenomeno delle giovanili azzurre |url=https://www.lastampa.it/2017/08/14/sport/litalia-ha-il-suo-mamba-la-storia-di-nico-mannion-fenomeno-delle-giovanili-azzurre-fA4EOLFEezmgTsLco7Wz3L/pagina.html |website=[[La Stampa]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |language=Italian |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frangipani |first1=Niccol\u00f2 |title=Astri Nascenti nel Basket: Nico Mannion, the italian stallion |url=http://www.vita-sportiva.it/2018/08/11/nico-mannion-the-italian-stallion/ |publisher=Vita Sportiva |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> Most notably, he helped Italian club [[Pallacanestro Cant\u00f9]] win the [[1990\u201391 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|1991 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]].<ref name=Snub/> Mannion's mother, Gaia Bianchi, is a former [[volleyball]] player who played for the [[Italy women's national volleyball team|Italian national volleyball team]].<ref name=\"Boivin\">{{cite web |last1=Boivin |first1=Paola |title=Boivin: Pinnacle freshman Nico Mannion creating national buzz |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2016/12/14/boivin-pinnacle-prodigy-mannion-creating-buzz-nice-pace-basketball/95442212/ |website=[[The Arizona Republic]] |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |date=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://arizonawildcats.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/nico-mannion/10611 Arizona Wildcats bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mannion, Nico}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Italian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Italian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Siena]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Phrasing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nico_Mannion"}
{"title_page": "Jay Dasilva", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Jay Dasilva\n|image               = \n|image_size          = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = Jay Rhys Dasilva<ref>{{cite web |title=Premier League clubs publish retained lists |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/408901 |publisher=Premier League |date=9 June 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|4|22|df=y}}<ref name=11v11>{{cite web |title=Jay Dasilva |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/jay-dasilva-253784/ |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_place         = [[Luton]], England\n|height              = {{convert|1.70|m|order=flip}}<ref name=11v11/>\n|position            = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|currentclub         = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|clubnumber          = 3\n|youthyears1         = 2007\u20132012\n|youthclubs1         = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n|youthyears2         = 2012\u20132016\n|youthclubs2         = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|years1              = 2016\u20132019\n|clubs1              = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|caps1               = 0\n|goals1              = 0\n|years2              = 2017\n|clubs2              = \u2192 [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] (loan)\n|caps2               = 10\n|goals2              = 0\n|years3              = 2017\u20132018\n|clubs3              = \u2192 [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] (loan)\n|caps3               = 38\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 2018\u20132019\n|clubs4              = \u2192 [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (loan)\n|caps4               = 28\n|goals4              = 0\n|years5              = 2019\u2013\n|clubs5              = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|caps5               = 13\n|goals5              = 0\n|nationalyears1      = 2012\u20132013\n|nationalteam1       = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n|nationalcaps1       = 4\n|nationalgoals1      = 0\n|nationalyears2      = 2013\u20132015\n|nationalteam2       = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n|nationalcaps2       = 21\n|nationalgoals2      = 1\n|nationalyears3      = 2015\u20132016\n|nationalteam3       = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n|nationalcaps3       = 4\n|nationalgoals3      = 0\n|nationalyears4      = 2016\u20132017\n|nationalteam4       = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n|nationalcaps4       = 15\n|nationalgoals4      = 0\n|nationalyears5      = 2017\u20132018\n|nationalteam5       = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]\n|nationalcaps5       = 6\n|nationalgoals5      = 0\n|nationalyears6      = 2018\u2013\n|nationalteam6       = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n|nationalcaps6       = 13\n|nationalgoals6      = 0\n|club-update         = 23:33, 25 February 2020 (UTC)\n|nationalteam-update = 23:33, 25 February 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Jay Rhys Dasilva''' (born 22 April 1998) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for {{English football updater|BristolC}} club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and the [[England national under-21 football team|England national under-21 team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Chelsea===\nDasilva joined Chelsea from [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in 2012, aged just thirteen,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/chelsea-transfer-news-jay-dasilva-fee-academy-bristol-city-rumours-gossip-latest-a8977011.html|title=Bristol City complete signing of Chelsea starlet Jay Dasilva|date=27 June 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref> and was quickly integrated into the club's youth setup, making his under-18 debut as an under-15 the following year. The following season, he made 23 appearances for the youth team, including scoring in the [[2013\u201314 FA Youth Cup]] final first leg against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/fa-youth-cup-final-fulham-3-chelsea-2-dembele-inspires-fightback-as-fulham-win-first-leg-9299590.html|title=FA Youth Cup Final - Fulham 3 Chelsea 2: Dembele inspires fightback as|date=28 April 2014|website=The Independent|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his second full season with the under-18s, Dasilva won the [[2014\u201315 FA Youth Cup]], as well as the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Youth League]], playing all but one game in the UEFA Youth League. He signed his first professional contract in July 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.squawka.com/news/chelsea-sign-jay-dasilva-to-a-professional-contract/415188|title=Chelsea sign Jay Da Silva to a professional contract|date=10 July 2015|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=Squawka}}</ref> having forced himself into Chelsea's under-21 side, where he established himself as a key player over the next year. He became one of the only players in history to win three [[FA Youth Cup]]s, alongside teammate [[Jake Clarke-Salter]] and five of the famed [[Busby Babes]], when he was part of the Chelsea side that lifted the [[2015\u201316 FA Youth Cup]].<ref name=\"Chelsea Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/teams/on-loan-players/jay-dasilva.html|title=Jay Dasilva|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref> He was also a member of the Chelsea side that claimed the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Youth League]], however he was an unused substitute in the final victory against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|PSG]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000699/match=2019575/index.html|title=Chelsea defeat Paris to retain Youth League title|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>\n\n====Charlton Athletic (loan)====\nOn 30 December 2016, Dasilva was loaned to [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2016/12/charlton-loan-move-for-dasilva.html|title=Charlton loan move for Dasilva|date=30 December 2016|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref> He made his debut for ''The Addicks'' on 14 January 2017, coming on as a substitute for [[Lewis Page]] against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]. He was brought on in the 28th minute, but was later substituted in the 80th minute of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38539095|title=Charlton Athletic 0\u20130 Millwall|date=14 January 2017|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 4 April 2017, Dasilva was given his first start for Charlton by manager [[Karl Robinson]], in their 2\u20130 home defeat against [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]], featuring for the entire 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Charlton Athletic 0\u20132 Milton Keynes Dons |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39312460 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 April 2017 |accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July 2017, Dasilva signed a new contract with Chelsea until 2021 and rejoined Charlton Athletic for a second loan spell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2017/07/new-deal-and-loan-for-dasilva.html|title=New deal and loan for Dasilva|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=21 July 2017|publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2018, Dasilva was voted the 2017\u201318 Fans Player of the Year.<ref name=\"Charltonpoty\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cafc.co.uk/news/view/5af08928d8cc1/jay-dasilva-named-201718-player-of-the-year|title=Jay Dasilva named 2017/18 Player of the Year|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018|publisher=Charlton Athletic F.C.}}</ref>\n\n===Bristol City===\nOn 9 August 2018, Dasilva joined [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] on a season long loan from Chelsea.<ref>[https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/city-sign-chelsea-defender-dasilva/ City sign Chelsea defender Dasilva] [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]. 9 August 2018. Retrieved 9 August 2018.</ref> He signed for Bristol City permanently on 26 June 2019 on a four-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/bristol-city-confirm-return-jay-3023999|title=Bristol City confirm return of Jay Dasilva on permanent deal from Chelsea|date=26 June 2019|accessdate=26 June 2019|first=Gregor|last=MacGregor|newspaper=Bristol Post}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDasilva has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]],<ref name=\"FA Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players?p=354511|title=Profile|accessdate=14 January 2017|publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]],<ref>{{cite web |title=England's matches: The under 19's: 2010\u201320 |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU19pg2.html |website=England Football Online |publisher=Chris Goodwin, Glen Isherwood & Peter Young |date=20 November 2019 |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]]<ref>{{cite web |title=England's matches: The under 20's |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU20.html |website=England Football Online |publisher=Chris Goodwin, Glen Isherwood & Peter Young |date=20 November 2019 |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] youth levels.<ref>{{cite web |title=England's matches: The under 21's: 2010\u201320 |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU21pg4.html |website=England Football Online |publisher=Chris Goodwin, Glen Isherwood & Peter Young |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was called up to the England under-16 team shortly after joining Chelsea's youth ranks for a [[Victory Shield]] game against [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dunstabletoday.co.uk/sport/football/hatters/england-u16-call-for-chelsea-s-former-hatters-starlet-1-4530821 |title=England U16 call for Chelsea's former Hatters starlet |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |publisher=Dunstable Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20497968 |title=Phil Neville on the importance of the England youth team |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |publisher=BBC Sport |author=Phil McNulty}}</ref> He made 4 appearances in total at this age level.<ref name=\"FA Profile\"/>\n\nHe was later called up to the England under-17 team for [[2015 UEFA European Under-17 Championship qualification]] in 2014. He scored his first and only goal at this age group, described as a 'brilliant solo effort', in a 3\u20131 victory over [[France national under-17 football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/news/newsid=2174257.html |title=England show champion form with France |date=30 October 2014 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> He maintained his place in the squad for [[2015 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|the full tournament]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2015/apr/22/england-u17s-squad-named-for-uefa-european-championship-in-bulgaria-220415 |title=John Peacock Names his England Under-17s Group |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |work=The FA}}</ref> and played in every game as England were knocked out by eventual semi-finalists [[Russia national under-17 football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2015/matches/round=2000665/match=2016633/postmatch/report/index.html#russia+england+reign |title=Tataev strikes as Russia end England reign |date=16 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> His last match for the under-17s came in a 0\u20130 draw with [[South Korea national under-17 football team|South Korea]] at the [[2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2015/oct/23/report-england-u17s-v-south-korea-world-cup-chile-231015|title=Korea 0-0 England: FIFA U17 World Cup Group B match report|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"FA Profile\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, Dasilva was called up to the England under-19 team for [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/home/news/2017/mar/16/england-under-19s-squad-160317 |title=Keith Downing Finalises Squad to Play Norway, Spain and Belarus at SGP |date=16 March 2017 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |work=The FA}}</ref> In July 2017, Dasilva captained the England under-19 team to victory at the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]].<ref name=\"U19 Champion\">{{cite web|title=European Under-19 Championship: England beat Portugal in final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40619862|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 July 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 2019, Dasilva was included in England's 23-man squad for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=ENGLAND U21S SQUAD NAMED BY AIDY BOOTHROYD FOR THIS SUMMER'S EURO FINALS IN ITALY|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2019/may/26/england-u21s-squad-named-for-euros-270519|publisher=The FA|date=27 May 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 25 February 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Chelsea F.C. season|2016\u20131