{"title_page": "Cyril Smith", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name = Cyril Smith\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MStJ|MBE|DL}}\n| image = CyrilSmith_cropped.jpg\n| caption = Smith addressing the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party Assembly]] in 1987\n| alt = \n| office = [[Liberal Chief Whip]]\n| term_start = 7 July 1976\n| term_end = 1977\n| leader = [[David Steel]]\n| predecessor = [[David Steel]]\n| successor = [[Alan Beith]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]]\n| parliament1 = United Kingdom\n| majority1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Jack McCann]]\n| successor1 = [[Liz Lynne]]\n| term_start1 = 26 October 1972\n| term_end1 = 9 April 1992\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1928|6|28}} \n| birth_place = [[Rochdale]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2010|9|3|1928|6|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Rochdale, [[Greater Manchester]], England\n| nationality = British\n| height = 6 ft 2 in\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] (1945\u20131951; 1970\u20131988)<br />[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (1952\u20131966)<br />[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] (1966\u20131970)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (1988\u20132010)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Politician\n| profession =\n|signature=Cyril smith signature.png}}\n'''Sir Cyril Smith''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE|MStJ|DL}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alamy.com/feb-02-1976-order-of-st-john-investiture-ceremony-at-the-grand-priory-image69483271.html |title=Stock Photo - Feb. 02, 1976 - Order of St. John Investiture Ceremony At The Grand Priory Church - Clerkenwell; Over 130 members of the Order of St. John and the St. John Ambulshos |last=Limited |first=Alamy |website=Alamy |access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51558 |date=13 December 1988 |page=13986}}</ref> (28 June 1928&nbsp;\u2013 3 September 2010) was a British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]]. After his death, numerous allegations of [[child sexual abuse]] by Smith emerged (including many made during his lifetime), leading the police to believe that Smith was a [[Sex offender|serial sex offender]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20516533 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Former MP sexually abused boys, police say |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nSmith was first active in local politics as a Liberal in 1945 before switching to [[Labour Party (United Kingdom)|Labour]] in 1950; he served as a Labour councillor in [[Rochdale]] from 1950 and became mayor in 1966. He subsequently switched parties again and entered Parliament as a Liberal in 1972, winning his Rochdale seat on five further occasions. Smith was appointed the [[Liberal Chief Whip]] in June 1975 but later resigned on health grounds. In his later years as an MP, Smith opposed an [[SDP\u2013Liberal Alliance|alliance]] with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and did not stand for re-election in 1992, but remained loyal to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] upon the parties' merger. Throughout much of his career, he maintained a high profile in the media, and became a well-known public figure.\n\nIn later years, his public esteem was considerably marred by the allegation that he had been involved in a cover-up of a health risk at a local [[asbestos]] factory. In 2008, there were calls for Smith to be stripped of his [[knighthood]] after it was revealed that he had asked the asbestos company [[Turner & Newall]] to prepare a speech for him in 1981, in which he declared: \"the public at large are not at risk from asbestos\".<ref name=\"DanczukBaker2014\">{{cite book |author1=Simon Danczuk |author2=Matthew Baker |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRSuAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT128 |date=15 April 2014 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |isbn=978-1-84954-730-7 |page=128}}</ref> It was later revealed that Smith owned 1,300 shares in the company. In 2008, Smith said that 4,000 asbestos-related deaths a year in the UK was \"relatively low\".<ref name=\"Howker\">{{cite news |last=Howker |first=Ed |work=[[New Statesman]] |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/health/2008/08/asbestos-victims-company |title=Asbestos: The lies that killed |accessdate=15 May 2009 |date=28 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following allegations of child abuse, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] formally admitted that Smith should have been charged with the sexual abuse of boys during his lifetime. [[Greater Manchester Police]] (GMP) said the boys \"were victims of physical and sexual abuse\" by Smith.<ref name=\"Dodd\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/cyril-smith-claims-decision-prosecute |title=Cyril Smith abuse claims: 'decision not to prosecute would not be made today' |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 November 2012 |last1=Dodd |first1=Vikram |last2=Syal |first2=Rajeev |location=London |publisher=Guardian News and Media}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20516533 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Former MP sexually abused boys, police say |publisher=BBC News |date=27 November 2012 |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> In November 2012, GMP Assistant Chief Constable Steve Heywood said there was \"overwhelming evidence\" that young boys were sexually and physically abused by Smith.<ref name=\"police1\">{{cite web |title=Statement regarding Sir Cyril Smith |url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/Content/WebsitePages/A22934C753EF3F0380257AC300607543?OpenDocument |publisher=Greater Manchester Police |accessdate=29 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203091905/http://www.gmp.police.uk/Content/WebsitePages/A22934C753EF3F0380257AC300607543?OpenDocument |archivedate=3 December 2012  }}</ref> In April 2014, it was reported that there had been 144 complaints against Smith from victims as young as eight, but attempts to prosecute him had always been blocked. Public authorities including [[Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|Rochdale Borough Council]], the police and intelligence services have been implicated in covering up Smith's crimes.<ref name=\"harrison1\">{{cite news |last=Harrison |first=Jody |title=Seven new child abuse claims against Cyril Smith |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/crime-courts/seven-new-child-abuse-claims-against-cyril-smith.23946227 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |newspaper=Sunday Herald |location=Glasgow |date=13 April 2014}}</ref> In 2015, it emerged that Smith had been arrested in the early 1980s in relation to these offences, but a high-level cover-up reportedly led to his being released within hours, the evidence destroyed and the investigating officers prevented from discussing the matter under the [[Official Secrets Act]].<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31908431 |title=Cyril Smith child abuse inquiry 'scrapped after his arrest'|publisher=BBC News |date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nSmith was born in Rochdale, [[Lancashire]], and described himself as \"illegitimate, deprived and poor.\"<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/politics-obituaries/7980251/Sir-Cyril-Smith.html |title=Sir Cyril Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref> Though he never knew the name of his father, he commented \"I suspect I know who he was.\"<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\"/> He lived with his mother, two illegitimate half-siblings, Eunice and Norman, and his grandmother in a [[Two-up two-down|one-up one-down cottage]] (now demolished) on Falinge Road. His mother, Eva Smith, worked in service to a local cotton mill\u2013owning family who lived at 8 Kilnerdyne Terrace.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977|p=18}}</ref>\n\nSmith was educated at [[Balderstone Technology College|Rochdale Grammar School for Boys]] and after leaving began work at Rochdale [[Inland Revenue]] Tax Office. In the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], aged 16, he gave a public speech in support of Liberal candidate Charles Harvey. Smith said he was given an ultimatum by his manager in the tax office to either choose the civil service or politics.\n\nHe left his job at the tax office and then worked as an office boy at Fothergill & Harvey's mill in [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]], northeast of Rochdale. The mill was owned by the Harveys, a notable Liberal family, but Smith claimed<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977|p=49}}</ref> the director Charles Harvey knew nothing of the job application by the young man who had lost his job for his public speech in favour of Harvey's Liberal candidature.<ref>''[[Rochdale Observer]]'' p17, 24 June 1996</ref>\n\nHe was a lifelong member of the [[Unitarianism|Rochdale Unitarian Church]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes flood in for Sir Cyril |url=http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/46608/tributes-flood-in-for-sir-cyril |accessdate=13 November 2016 |publisher=Rochdale Online |date=3 September 2010}}</ref> Contemporaries remembered him expressing, as a teenager, the desire to be both mayor and MP.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=letter to \"Lives Remembered\" |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2719326.ece |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=[[The Times]] |date=9 September 2010}}</ref> He served in many roles, including as Sunday School superintendent, trustee, and chair of the trustees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peel |first1=Gillian (Rev.) |title=SIR CYRIL SMITH MBE |url=http://www.nufonline.org.uk/NewNUF09/pdfs/NL392.pdf |accessdate=13 November 2016 |issue=392 |publisher=National Unitarian Fellowship |date=November\u2013December 2010}}</ref> His Unitarian faith intersected with his Liberal politics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenyon |first1=Neville |title=Letters: Sir Cyril Smith obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2010/sep/14/sir-cyril-smith-obituary-letters |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=14 September 2010}}</ref> Smith credited the church with \"helping develop his fiercely independent and anti-establishment streak\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Danczuk |first1=Simon |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Early career===\nSmith joined the Liberal Party in 1945 and was a member of the National Executive Committee of the [[National League of Young Liberals|Young Liberals]] in 1948 and 1949. From 1948 to 1950, he was Liberal agent in [[Stockport (UK Parliament constituency)|Stockport]], but after the poor general election results experienced by the Liberal Party [[1950 United Kingdom general election|in 1950]] and [[1951 United Kingdom general election|1951]] he was advised by the losing Liberal candidate for Stockport, Reg Hewitt, to join the Labour Party.\n\nIn 1952, Smith was elected a Labour Party councillor for the Falinge ward of Rochdale. By 1954, he was chairman of Rochdale Council's Establishment Committee. In 1963 he switched committee roles to be responsible for Estates which included overseeing residential and town centre development.\n\nHe was appointed the Labour Mayor of Rochdale in 1966, with his mother, Eva, acting as mayoress (she retained her job as a cleaner in [[Rochdale Town Hall]] whilst in the post). In her work as a cleaner at the town hall, she was banned from entering the police station \u2013 likewise based in the building \u2013 for she would search through its bins for information to help her son.{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=208}}\n\nSmith's mayoral duties were filmed for the BBC's ''[[Man Alive (BBC TV series)|Man Alive]]'' documentary series, in an episode titled \"Santa Claus for a Year\".{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=55}} In 1966 he was appointed chairman of the Education Committee overseeing the introduction of [[comprehensive education]] in the district. In the same year he was appointed Member of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]]. According to his autobiography,{{sfn|Smith|1977|p=107}} Smith was found guilty of an offence relating to public lotteries and bound over to keep the peace for 12 months.\n\nIn 1966, Smith resigned the Labour [[whip (politics)|whip]] when the party refused to vote for an increase in [[council house]] rents and sat with four other councillors as independents until 1970. His subsequent return to the Liberal Party, and his election as a Liberal MP, caused surprise after his role in opposing [[Ludovic Kennedy]], the Liberal candidate in the [[1958 Rochdale by-election]]. Controversy was sparked by Rochdale Liberals when the parliamentary candidate, Garth Pratt, was deselected to make way for Smith's return to the party.\n\nDuring the 1960s Smith was active on many Rochdale Council committees regarding youth activities. These included: Rochdale Youth Orchestra, Rochdale Youth Theatre Workshop, governorship of 29 Rochdale schools and chairmanship of the Youth Committee, Youth Employment Committee and the Education Committee.{{sfn|Smith|1977|p=101}}\n\n===Member of Parliament===\nHaving been Liberal candidate in [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] at the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]] when he took the party to second place, Smith won the seat at the [[1972 Rochdale by-election|1972 by-election]] with a large swing from Labour to the Liberals, and a majority of 5,171.\n\nHe was appointed as the party Chief Whip in June 1975, and faced pressure from the press in the wake of a scandal involving party leader [[Jeremy Thorpe]]. Smith was in hospital when Thorpe sacked him, just before himself being forced to resign.<ref name=\"Meadowcroft\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/sir-cyril-smith-obituary |title=Sir Cyril Smith obituary |work=The Guardian |date=3 September 2010 |last=Meadowcroft |first=Michael |location=London}}</ref> Speaking to [[Granada Television]] in 2003, [[David Steel]] reflected on events in the 1970s with the conclusion: \"Cyril was not an ideal Chief Whip because he did not handle a crisis well and had a tendency to say anything to a news camera.\"<ref>\"Nice One Cyril\" [[ITV Granada]]. Broadcast date 22 June 2003</ref> He was the only Liberal MP during his parliamentary career to oppose abortion and advocate the return of the death penalty.<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\"/><ref>Oliver Kamm [http://timesopinion.tumblr.com/post/35705574839/the-small-mind-of-sir-cyril-smith-paedophile \"The small mind of Sir Cyril Smith, paedophile\"], ''The Times'' (Opinion blog), 14 November 2012</ref> One of his constituents was jailed for 16 years for [[Murder of Lesley Molseed|the sexual murder of a child]], in what turned out to be a miscarriage of justice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McSmith |first1=Andy |title=Miscarriage of justice corrected as jury finds man guilty of murder |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/miscarriage-of-justice-corrected-as-jury-finds-man-guilty-of-murder-400089.html |accessdate=13 November 2016 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=13 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A terrible crime with two victims |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/a-terrible-crime-with-two-victims-1047375 |accessdate=13 November 2016 |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=13 August 2010}}</ref> The man's mother repeatedly approached Smith for help, but he declined to take the case on.<ref>''Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith''. \"Silent Voices #3\".</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Smith approached former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Prime Minister of the UK|Prime Minister]] [[Ted Heath]] to discuss forming a new centre party. In 1980, Smith described UK unemployment figures of two million jobless people as \"a disgrace\". Smith said: \"They represent a sick society, and are not acceptable to live with.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=McBain |first=Barclay |title=Smith attacks Government over jobless 'disgrace' |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AsRAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3053,2354670&dq=smith+attacks+government&hl=en |accessdate=14 July 2013 |newspaper=The Glasgow Herald |date=11 September 1980}}</ref> In 1981, Smith was involved in moves to create \"a party with a new image\" but, according to the ''[[Rochdale Observer]]'', at the foundation of the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in 1981 he warned Liberal Party colleagues to move with caution. Smith was quoted as being \"opposed to an alliance at any price\".<ref>''Rochdale Observer'', 24 June 1996</ref> He would later express the view that the Liberal Party would have been \"better off\" without being \"shackled to the SDP\".<ref name=\"menmedia\" /> After [[David Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]'s 1988 bill to reduce the time limit for abortions was talked out by MPs, he referred to other members as \"murderers in the womb\". The speaker of the House of Commons forced him to apologise for the comment.<ref name=\"Kamm2010\">{{cite news |url=http://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/oliver-kamm/35504/gross/ |title=Gross |work=The Times |location=London |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=1 February 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n===Asbestos===\nIn 2008 the ''[[New Statesman]]'' accused him of improper conduct in his connection with the company [[Turner & Newall]] (T&N), which was based in his constituency, and was once the world's largest manufacturer of materials using [[asbestos]].<ref name=\"Howker\"/> In the summer recess of 1981, Smith wrote to Sydney Marks, head of personnel at T&N, informing him that EEC regulations were coming up for debate in the next parliamentary session. A House of Commons speech he delivered was almost identical to one prepared for him by the company.<ref name=\"Howker\"/> \"The public at large are not at risk\" he said in his speech of a substance then long known as lethal if inhaled.<ref name=\"Howker\"/> A year later Smith revealed he owned 1,300 shares in the company.<ref name=\"Meadowcroft\"/> Interviewed in September 2008 by the BBC's local news programme, he responded to the claims he had helped cover up the dangers of asbestos as \"absolute rubbish\".<ref>[http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/21/spodden-valley/13616/sir-cyril-smith-defends-himself-on-bbc-news \"Sir Cyril Smith defends himself on BBC News\"], ''Rochdale News'', 4 September 2008. See also Alice McKeegan [http://menmedia.co.uk/rochdaleobserver/news/s/1065028_cyril_there_was_no_cover_up_on_asbestos \"Cyril: There was no cover up on asbestos\"], ''Manchester Evening News'', 2 September 2012</ref> After Smith's death, he was described by journalist [[Oliver Kamm]] in his blog in ''[[The Times]]'' as \"a corrupt, mendacious mountain of flesh\".<ref name=\"Kamm2010\"/>\n\nThe controversy led in November 2008 to a parliamentary [[early day motion]] calling for Smith to be stripped of the knighthood he had been granted in 1988.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/2470 EDM 2470], parliament.uk website, 11 November 2008</ref> [[Kevin Maguire (journalist)|Kevin Maguire]] of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' supported the motion.<ref>[http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/16086/national-newspaper-calls-for-sir-cyril-to-lose-knighthood \"National newspaper calls for Sir Cyril to lose knighthood\"], ''Rochdale Online'', 5 November 2008</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nAfter leaving Westminster and the death of his mother Eva in 1994, Smith was invited by a lifelong friend, the public relations manager at [[Cunard Line|Cunard]], to become a guest lecturer on the [[QE2]] cruise liner.<ref>''Lancashire Life'', June 1998</ref> He liked to spend his holidays at [[Lytham St Annes]], a seaside resort near Blackpool.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Chris |title=Sir Cyril Smith \u2013 A personal note from Rochdale Euro-MP Chris Davies |url=http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/46629/sir-cyril-smith-%E2%80%93-a-personal-note-from-rochdale-euromp-chris |accessdate=13 November 2016 |publisher=Rochdale Online |date=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006, Smith was taken to hospital after collapsing at his Rochdale home. He had been weakened by dehydration and low [[potassium]] levels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sir Cyril 'recovering' after fall |date=18 February 2006 |accessdate=20 November 2012 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/4727424.stm |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nSmith died of cancer in a Rochdale nursing home on 3 September 2010.<ref name=\"menmedia\">{{cite news |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1315976_former_rochdale_mp_sir_cyril_smith_dies_at_age_of_82 |title=Tributes to Sir Cyril Smith, a giant of politics |work=Manchester Evening News |publisher=M.E.N. Media |date=3 September 2010 |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> Smith had made detailed plans for his own funeral. It was held in the Great Hall of Rochdale Town Hall, and those who spoke included [[David Alton]], the MEP [[Chris Davies (Liberal Democrat politician)|Chris Davies]], and former MP [[Paul Rowen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rochdale says goodbye to Sir Cyril Smith|url=https://rochdalelibdems.org.uk/en/article/2010/0091439/rochdale-says-goodbye-to-sir-cyril-smith|website=Rochdale Liberal Democrats|accessdate=13 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114170953/https://rochdalelibdems.org.uk/en/article/2010/0091439/rochdale-says-goodbye-to-sir-cyril-smith|archivedate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Of all the many tributes, the then-current leader of Rochdale Council summed him up: \"He simply was politics for Rochdale.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Cyril Smith: Tributes pour in|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/sir-cyril-smith-tributes-pour-898296|accessdate=13 November 2016|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> The service was led by the minister of his local Unitarian church, of which he had been a lifelong member.<ref>[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/remembrance-service-for-sir-cyril-900673 Remembrance service for Sir Cyril] ''Manchester Evening News'' 8 October 2010</ref>\n\nHis younger brother Norman followed him into local politics, as councillor, mayor, and president of the local Liberal Democrat chapter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norman Smith MBE named as new Lib Dem President|url=http://rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/49734/norman-smith-mbe-named-as-new-lib-dem-president|accessdate=13 November 2016|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Popular image==\nSmith's large size and capacity for blunt speaking and popular touch made him one of the most recognisable British politicians of the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"menmedia\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11180264 BBC News, \"Former Liberal Democrat MP Cyril Smith dies\", 3 September 2010]. Retrieved 17 March 2015</ref> His nickname, \"Big Cyril\", was the title of his autobiography.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977}}</ref> He made many popular television appearances: he sang \"She's a Lassie from Lancashire\" on his friend [[Jimmy Savile]]'s early-1970s TV show ''Clunk Click'',<ref>{{cite news |title='Paedophiles' Cyril Smith & Jimmy Savile Were Friends For 40 Years |last=Nelson |first=Sara C |work=Huffington Post |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/29/paedophiles-cyril-smith-jimmy-savile-friends-_n_2210121.html |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> appeared in an advert for a \"greatest hits\" album by 1980s pop group [[Bananarama]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16941969 |title=Lembit Opik stars in unsigned band's music video |publisher=BBC News |date=8 February 2012 |accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> and sang a duet with [[Don Estelle]] in a 1999 recording of the [[Laurel and Hardy]] song \"[[The Trail of the Lonesome Pine (song)|The Trail of the Lonesome Pine]]\".<ref name=\"obituary\">Don Estelle obituary. ''The Independent'', 4 August 2003 {{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref> Like several other prominent British MPs in the 1980s, he was regularly parodied in the satirical television show ''[[Spitting Image]]''.{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=11}}\n\nHe is believed to have been the heaviest British MP ever: at 6'2\" (188&nbsp;cm) he was reported to weigh 29 [[stone (Imperial mass)|stone]] 12 pounds, about 190 kilogrammes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochdale-makes-its-mark-at-last-to-the-regret-of-mr-brown-1958907.html |title=Rochdale makes its mark at last, to the regret of Mr Brown |date=30 April 2010 |work=The Independent |accessdate=5 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref> A common joke on the size of the Parliamentary Liberal Party in the early 1970s was that only one taxi would be needed to transport the entire party; after Smith's election, the party could fill two taxis.<ref>BBC Nationwide 1972</ref>\n\nA lifelong bachelor, Smith told ''[[You (British magazine)|You]]'' magazine: \"I haven't had a lot of time for courting women&nbsp;... I've tended to be married to politics\".<ref name=\"menmedia\" /><ref>''You'' magazine: 9 May 1993</ref> It was later alleged that he sexually assaulted adolescent boys.<ref name=elm/> He was a friend of the mother of broadcasters [[Andy Kershaw|Andy]] and [[Liz Kershaw]]; she described him as dependent on [[Diazepam|Valium]], but he denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beattie |first1=Jason |title=Sir Cyril Smith dies aged 82 - but was there a darker side to the former MP? |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sir-cyril-smith-dies-aged-245375 |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of child sexual abuse==\n\n===Early allegations===\nIn May 1979, a local [[underground magazine]], the ''Rochdale Alternative Press'', alleged that in the 1960s Smith had spanked and sexually abused teenage boys in a hostel he co-founded. The matter was investigated by the police but Smith was not prosecuted. The story was repeated in the same month by the satirical magazine ''[[Private Eye]]''.<ref>''Private Eye'' No. 454 (11 May 1979), p. 3.</ref> Smith never publicly denied the accusations of abuse, nor did he ever take legal action, but after his death the allegations were denied by his family.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1328218_cyrils_family_in_fury_at_cowardly_article |title=Cyril's family in fury at 'cowardly' article |work=Manchester Evening News |date=17 September 2010 |last=Storey |first=Katie |publisher=M.E.N. Media}}</ref><ref>[http://mooredge.com/mooredgenews.html \"Does Rochdale really want a LibDem MP??\"]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>Private Eye, No.1271. September 2010</ref> The Press Office of the leader of the Liberal Party, [[David Steel]] commented, \"All he seems to have done is spanked a few bare bottoms\".<ref>''Private Eye'' No. 1329 (14 December 2012), p. 10.</ref>\n\n===2012===\nIn November 2012, speaking in the House of Commons, [[Simon Danczuk]],<ref name = \"Danczuk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2012-11-13a.208.0&s |title=House of Commons, 13 November 2012, \"Backbench Business \u2014 Child Sexual Exploitation\", Simon Danczuk, 4.29pm |work=TheyWorkForYou.com, UK Parliament |date=13 November 2012}}</ref> the Labour [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for Rochdale, Smith's old seat, called for an inquiry into the alleged abuse.<ref name = \"Danczuk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20303606 |title=Rochdale MP calls for Cyril Smith 'indecent assault' inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Rossendale]] councillor Alan Neal said that at the age of 11 in 1964, during Smith's membership of the Labour Party, he was beaten by Smith at a hostel for boys.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20337495 |title=Councillor makes MP abuse claim |date=15 November 2012 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> Neal said: \"I'm speaking now because someone has taken a right decision to raise this issue with the authorities\". He added that he told police about the incident in 1968 when he left the school but on raising it \"everyone made the same comment that the person in question was a very important, powerful man\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20337495 |title=Councillor accuses Sir Cyril Smith of physical abuse |publisher=BBC News |date=15 November 2012 |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref> Neal said that he lost two front teeth and needed stitches to a head wound after Smith assaulted him for refusing to eat a potted meat sandwich.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former East Lancs mayor backs call for Sir Cyril Smith child abuse inquiry |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/11150749.Former_East_Lancs_mayor_backs_call_for_Sir_Cyril_Smith_child_abuse_inquiry/ |accessdate=26 April 2014 |newspaper=Lancashire Telegraph |date=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnother alleged victim of abuse by Smith waived his right to anonymity in November 2012 to claim that Smith smacked him and stroked his buttocks when he was a teenager at a Rochdale care home in the 1960s. Barry Fitton said he was spanked \"very, very hard\" by Smith and that he was left in tears by the alleged incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20329227 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Accuser 'left in tears' after 'abuse' |publisher=BBC News |date=14 November 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2012, [[Greater Manchester Police]] announced it would investigate allegations that Smith had sexually abused boys at a hostel in Rochdale after 1974, and [[Lancashire Police]] would investigate claims dating from before 1974. The police said it would look at whether investigations had taken place into Smith during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/policy-inquiry-launched-in-sir-cyril-smith-abuse-allegations |title=Policy inquiry launched in Sir Cyril Smith abuse allegations |work=Channel 4 News |date=21 November 2012 |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 2012, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] said that Smith should have been charged with crimes of abuse more than 40 years earlier. In a statement, Greater Manchester Police said the boys \"were victims of physical and sexual abuse\" by the ex-Rochdale MP. Smith was never charged although investigations were undertaken in 1970, 1998, and 1999. The method of assessing the probability of a conviction has changed since 1970, and the decision not to charge Smith then necessitated the outcome of the 1998 investigation. Following the sexual abuse allegations, Rochdale Council removed a [[blue plaque]] to Smith from the town hall.<ref name=\"Dodd\" /><ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nGreater Manchester Police Assistant Chief Constable Steve Heywood said: \"Although Smith cannot be charged or convicted posthumously, from the overwhelming evidence we have it is right and proper we should publicly recognise that young boys were sexually and physically abused\".<ref name=\"police1\"/>\n\nOn 28 November 2012, an alleged victim of sexual abuse by Smith waived his right to anonymity in a television interview with [[Sky News]] to say that he was sexually abused by Smith at a council-run residential special school. Chris Marshall broke down in tears during his interview when describing the sexual abuse he said took place at Knowl View school in Rochdale in the early 1980s. He said that as a nine-year-old boy he was taken to a room and made to perform oral sex on Smith and one other man. Smith was a governor at the school and allegedly had his own set of keys. Liberal Democrat leader [[Nick Clegg]] said: \"I am deeply shocked and horrified by these terrible allegations and my thoughts are with the victims who had the courage to speak out\".<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Mike |title=Cyril Smith: Former MP 'Abused Me As A Child' |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1017895/cyril-smith-former-mp-abused-me-as-a-child |accessdate=14 July 2013 |publisher=Sky News |date=28 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Tony Robinson, a former [[Special Branch]] officer with Lancashire Police in the 1970s, said that a dossier of sexual abuse allegations against Smith which police claimed was \"lost\" was actually seized by [[MI5]]. Robinson said that he was asked by MI5 to send to London a police dossier that had been kept in a safe in his office which he said was \"thick\" with allegations from boys claiming they had been abused by Smith.<ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |title=Sir Cyril Smith sex abuse dossier seized by MI5 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/9678697/Sir-Cyril-Smith-sex-abuse-dossier-seized-by-MI5.html |accessdate=29 March 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Rochdale MP Simon Danczuk alleged that Smith raped some of his victims. Danczuk said: \"There is no doubt that Cyril Smith seriously sexually abused young boys: why the CPS didn't prosecute more recently is puzzling\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Cyril Smith 'raped some of his victims', MP says |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20568253 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing claims by MP [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] of \"a powerful paedophile network linked to Parliament and No 10\", it was reported that Scotland Yard detectives investigating [[Elm Guest House claims and controversy|allegations of child abuse at the Elm Guest House]] were looking into allegations that senior politicians abused children in the 1980s and escaped justice.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/scotland-yard-investigating-allegations-senior-politicians-abused-children-in-the-1980s-and-used-connections-to-escape-justice-8411989.html |author=Hickman, Martin |title=Scotland Yard investigating allegations senior politicians abused children in the 1980s and used 'connections' to escape justice |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=12 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn January 2013, ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' reported that police were investigating claims that Smith sexually abused boys at the London guest house.<ref>{{cite news |first1=James |last1=Hanning |first2=Paul |last2=Cahalan |title=Cyril Smith named in Barnes abuse case |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/cyril-smith-named-in-barnes-abuse-case-8468370.html |accessdate=24 March 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent on Sunday]] |location=London |date=27 January 2013}}</ref> A spokesman for the Metropolitan Police later said: \"We can confirm Cyril Smith visited the premises.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Sir Cyril Smith 'visited alleged sex abuse guest house' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-24074818 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 September 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> A 16-year-old boy was allegedly sexually abused by Smith at Elm Guest House.<ref name=elm>{{cite news |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |title='Influential' politician visited guest house at centre of child sex investigation |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10775360/Influential-politician-visited-guest-house-at-centre-of-child-sex-investigation.html |accessdate=9 July 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 April 2014}}</ref> MP [[Simon Danczuk]] said he was convinced that there was a \"network of paedophiles\" operating in the House of Commons who helped to protect Smith.<ref name=elm/>\n\nIn September 2013, a [[Channel 4]] ''[[Dispatches (TV programme)|Dispatches]]'' programme \"The Paedophile MP: How Cyril Smith Got Away With It\" quoted the Crown Prosecution Service as claiming that they had not prosecuted Smith for crimes of abuse because he had been given an assurance in 1970 that he would not be prosecuted, and that prevented them from subsequently reopening the investigation under the law at the time. Political journalist [[Francis Wheen]] said that he found this explanation incomprehensible.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dispatches: Episode Guide |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/dispatches/episode-guide |work=Channel 4.com |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nDanczuk, with researcher and campaigner Matthew Baker, published ''Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith'', an expos\u00e9 of the child abuse committed by Smith. Danczuk alleged that Smith was part of a high-level paedophile ring and that Smith had used his influence to escape prosecution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/smile-for-the-camera-hardback |title=Smile for the Camera |publisher=Biteback publishing |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Paedophile ring protected Sir Cyril Smith, MP claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27047442 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> Danczuk said: \"Once you looked beyond the jolly clown playing for the camera, there was a sickening, dark heart. This wasn't just about abuse, it was about power - and a cover-up that reached from Rochdale all the way to the very top of the Establishment.\"<ref name=\"harrison1\"/> Danczuk said that in the 1980s police discovered child pornography belonging to Smith, but he escaped justice.<ref name=Danczuk1>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=MP defends book on Cyril Smith |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/book-describes--ex-rochdale-mp-6990663 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=14 May 2014 |date=15 April 2014}}</ref> Danczuk described Smith as \"a predatory paedophile and a prolific offender who would target the most vulnerable boys.\" He said: \"A lot of manpower went into investigating Smith over the years, but the only thing he was ever convicted for was mis-selling a lottery ticket.\"<ref name=Danczuk1/>\n\nIn 2014, former Liberal leader Sir [[David Steel]] said he had confronted Smith about his \"unusual\" behaviour with boys at a hostel in Rochdale. Following allegations published in 1979, Steel said that Smith confessed to spanking boys and conducting intimate \"medical examinations\" on them but was allowed to remain as a Liberal MP. Steel said: \"I asked Cyril Smith about it. I was half expecting him to say it was all wrong, and I would have been urging him to sue to save his reputation. To my surprise he said the report was correct.\" Steel said that Smith had a supervisory role in institutions in Rochdale where he was involved in [[corporal punishment]]. Steel said of the abuse allegations: \"They had been investigated by the police, as ''Private Eye'' stated, and no action had been taken on them. So there was nothing more I could do.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |title=Cyril Smith admitted spanking and touching boys, but I let him stay, says Lord Steel |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10796546/Cyril-Smith-admitted-spanking-and-touching-boys-but-I-let-him-stay-says-Lord-Steel.html |accessdate=11 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, following reports that there had been 144 complaints against Smith and that attempts to prosecute him had always been blocked,<ref name=\"harrison1\"/> the President of the Liberal Democrats, [[Tim Farron]], said that his party needed to answer \"serious questions\" about who knew that Smith had faced allegations of sexual assault.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lib Dems face 'questions' over Cyril Smith abuse claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27166442 |publisher=BBC News |date=26 April 2014}}</ref> However, Liberal Democrat leader [[Nick Clegg]] refused to hold an inquiry into what he called the \"repugnant\" actions of Smith. Clegg said: \"My party, the Liberal Democrats, did not know about these actions.\" Clegg stated that the child abuse allegations were a matter for the police.<ref>{{cite news |last=Graham |first=Georgia |title=Nick Clegg refuses to hold inquiry into Cyril Smith child abuse allegations |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nick-clegg/10765504/Nick-Clegg-refuses-to-hold-inquiry-into-Cyril-Smith-child-abuse-allegations.html |accessdate=4 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, it was alleged that Smith had molested an 11-year-old boy at the [[National Liberal Club]] in London in 1978. Smith allegedly insisted that the boy remove his underpants before attempting to fondle him. A spokesman for the Liberal Democrats said: \"Cyril Smith's acts were vile and repugnant and we have nothing but sympathy for those whose lives he ruined.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Sammon |first=Gerry |title=Cyril Smith molested 11-year-old boy - claim |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/allegation-disgraced-former-rochdale-mp-7192245 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=30 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Detective Chief Superintendent Russ Jackson of Greater Manchester Police admitted the force's previous investigations into abuse linked to Smith at Rochdale Knowl View residential school \"fell well short\" of what would be expected today.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Jennifer |title=Police admit '90s probe into Knowl View abuse scandal 'fell well short' of today's standards |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/knowl-view-abuse-scandal-investigation-7259254 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=12 June 2014}}</ref> Allegations were made that a paedophile ring had been operating for decades in the town of Rochdale and that men from as far away as [[Sheffield]] were travelling to Rochdale to have sex with Knowl View boys aged between eight and thirteen.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thomas |first=Ed |title=Knowl View: Rochdale Council 'misled' police amid school abuse claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-27427952 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 June 2014}}</ref> Greater Manchester Police said there were 21 suspects, 14 of whom it had identified, including Smith.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cyril Smith sex abuse allegations: Seven men come forward |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-27427952 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In July 2014, Rochdale council's inquiry into child abuse linked to Smith at Knowl View residential school was halted at the request of police. Greater Manchester Police asked the authority to suspend their inquiry while detectives investigated claims of an institutional cover-up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Jennifer |title=Home Office could be called in to investigate 'child abuse cover-up' at Cyril Smith school |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/home-office-knowl-view-probe-7386381 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, it was reported that Smith had put pressure on the [[BBC]] in 1976, by asking the corporation not to investigate the \"private lives of certain MPs\". According to letters in the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|National Archives]], Smith wrote to BBC Director-General [[Charles Curran (broadcaster)|Sir Charles Curran]] in September 1976 saying he was \"deeply concerned about the investigative activities of the BBC\", especially relating to \"the private lives of certain MPs\". Former children's minister [[Tim Loughton]] described Smith's letters as \"bully-boy tactics\". Loughton said: \"It was an abuse of position that somebody as an MP was saying, 'You shouldn't look at us, we're above the law.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bateman |first=Tom |title=Cyril Smith 'put pressure on BBC' over investigating MPs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28093405 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nA report released by the Crown Prosecution Service in July 2014 showed that in 1970 a police detective investigating Smith presented evidence to his superior of Smith's abuse of young boys at a care home in Rochdale, but no action was taken.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Syal |first1=Rajeev |title=Cyril Smith: 'evidence of sex abuse' was overruled CPS report shows |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/16/cyril-smith-sex-abuse-cps-1970-report-lancashire-dpp |accessdate=17 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn March 2015, [[Cabinet Office]] papers were released confirming that Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] was made aware of allegations against Smith before he was knighted in 1988.<ref>{{cite news |title=Margaret Thatcher 'told of Cyril Smith abuse claims' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31789827 |accessdate=10 March 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=8 March 2015}}</ref> Shortly after, a BBC investigation on ''[[Newsnight]]'' revealed that Smith had been arrested in the early 1980s in relation to his participation in a paedophile ring, but a high-level cover-up reportedly led to him being released within hours, the evidence destroyed and the investigating officers prevented from discussing the matter under the [[Official Secrets Act]].<ref name=\"BBC News\"/> [[Theresa May]], the Home Secretary, called for immunity for whistle-blowers in the case.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/mar/17/home-secretary-theresa-may-cyril-smith-cover-up-claims-shocking-prosecutions |title=Home secretary: Cyril Smith cover-up claims 'could lead to prosecutions' |work=The Guardian |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Reports also emerged of Smith's arrest by [[Northamptonshire Police]], where he was again released in mysterious circumstances.<ref>{{cite news |title='Cyril Smith M1 arrest to be probed by Northamptonshire Police' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-31964255 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a retired police officer said that he was threatened with the [[Official Secrets Act]] after he found Smith in the home of a known sex offender, with two drunk teenage boys, and a police sergeant in civilian clothes. The retired officer said that he was summoned to a meeting with a senior officer at Stockport Police Station and told \"in no uncertain terms\" not to say anything about it. The alleged incident took place in 1988 at a house in Stockport after a complaint that the occupier had been committing a lewd act in his window in front of a newspaper boy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keeling |first=Neal |title=Former officers asked to help with investigation into the alleged cover up of child sex abuse linked to Cyril Smith |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/police-chief-asks-ex-cops-help-8896730 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn October 2017 the [[Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse]] (IICSA) was told that [[MI5]] had been made aware that prosecutors lied to the press over the existence of a child abuse file on Smith. Detectives had said the \"sordid\" claims about the late MP's alleged abuse of young boys in 1970 \"stood up\". The enquiry heard how the investigation into Smith had \"illuminated\" wider abuse suffered by the boys. In 1988, when Smith was made a knight, then Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] had probably been informed of his chequered past. The hearings focused on alleged offences at Cambridge House hostel and the Knowl View residential school in Rochdale, where Smith was a governor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41547471 |title=MI5 'told of Cyril Smith abuse case lie' |date=9 October 2017 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Cyril Smith was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in 1966.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* He was invested as a Serving Brother of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Order of St John]] in 1976.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/bright-knight-was-man-of-honours-898293 |title=Bright knight was man of honours |first=Manchester Evening |last=News |date=7 September 2010 |publisher= |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He served as [[Pro-vice-chancellor|Deputy Pro Chancellor]] of [[Lancaster University]] from 1978\u20131985.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scan.lusu.co.uk/index.php/2014/06/05/one-alumnus-that-should-not-have-kept-in-touch/ |title=One alumnus that should not have kept in touch |first=Daniel |last=Snape |date=5 June 2014 |publisher= |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* He was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1988, allowing him to be known as '''Sir Cyril Smith'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/cyril-smith-liberal-politics|title=Cyril Smith dies, 82 |first=Martin |last=Wainwright |date=3 September 2010 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He was appointed a [[Deputy lieutenant]] of [[Greater Manchester]] in 1991, allowing him the [[List of post-nominal letters (United Kingdom)|Post Nominal Letters]] \"DL\" for Life. \n* He was awarded the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Rochdale]] in November 1992. After a series of allegations of child sexual abuse, over a span of 30 years, came to light following his death, he was posthumously stripped of this honour by a unanimous vote of [[Rochdale Borough Council]] on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/123143/cyril-smith-stripped-of-the-freedom-of-borough |title=Cyril Smith stripped of the freedom of borough |website=www.rochdaleonline.co.uk |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He was awarded the [[Honorary degree]] of [[Doctor of Laws]] by Lancaster University in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/about-us/ourpeople/honorary-degrees/#nineties |title=Honorary Graduates - Lancaster University |first=Lancaster |last=University |website=www.lancaster.ac.uk |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|Greater Manchester|Politics|United Kingdom|Liberalism|Law}}\n* [[Westminster paedophile dossier]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Cyril |title=Big Cyril: Autobiography |year=1977 |publisher= |isbn=0-491-02261-1 |ref=harv}}\n* ''Reflections from Rochdale: As I Saw it and as I See it'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-85187-340-6}}. A later slimmer autobiographical work.\n* \"Cyril Smith\", entry by Tim Farron in Brack et al. (eds.) ''Dictionary of Liberal Biography'' (Politico's, 1998)\n* {{cite book |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |year=2014 |first=Simon |last=Danczuk |authorlink=Simon Danczuk |first2=Matthew |last2=Baker |publisher=Biteback |isbn=978-1-84954-644-7 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs|mr-cyril-smith|Cyril Smith}}\n* [http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/content_objectid=13671488_method=full_siteid=50061_headline=-Sir-Cyril-in-fight-against-assembly-name_page.html Sir Cyril in fight against assembly]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/sir-cyril-smith-obituary Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'']\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-cyril-smith-idiosyncratic-and-largerthanlife-liberal-politician-who-never-shied-away-from-falling-out-with-his-own-party-2070138.html Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'']\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/politics-obituaries/7980251/Sir-Cyril-Smith.html Obituary in ''The Telegraph'']\n* [http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/46629/sir-cyril-smith-%E2%80%93-a-personal-note-from-rochdale-euromp-chris Tribute in ''Rochdale Online''] by Chris Davies MEP\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par| uk}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Jack McCann]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] |years=[[1972 Rochdale by-election|1972]]\u2013[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Liz Lynne]] }}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[David Steel]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Liberal Chief Whip]] | years= 1976\u201377 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Alan Beith]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Child sexual abuse in the UK|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Cyril}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in England]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse cover-ups]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Rochdale]]\n[[Category:People from Rochdale]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Rochdale]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name = Cyril Smith\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MStJ|MBE|DL}}\n| image = CyrilSmith_cropped.jpg\n| caption = Smith addressing the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party Assembly]] in 1987\n| alt = \n| office = [[Liberal Chief Whip]]\n| term_start = 7 July 1976\n| term_end = 1977\n| leader = [[David Steel]]\n| predecessor = [[David Steel]]\n| successor = [[Alan Beith]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]]\n| parliament1 = United Kingdom\n| majority1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Jack McCann]]\n| successor1 = [[Liz Lynne]]\n| term_start1 = 26 October 1972\n| term_end1 = 9 April 1992\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1928|6|28}} \n| birth_place = [[Rochdale]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2010|9|3|1928|6|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Rochdale, [[Greater Manchester]], England\n| nationality = British\n| height = 6 ft 2 in\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] (1945\u20131951; 1970\u20131988)<br />[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] (1952\u20131966)<br />[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] (1966\u20131970)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (1988\u20132010)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Politician\n| profession =\n|signature=Cyril smith signature.png}}\n'''Sir Cyril Smith''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE|MStJ|DL}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alamy.com/feb-02-1976-order-of-st-john-investiture-ceremony-at-the-grand-priory-image69483271.html |title=Stock Photo - Feb. 02, 1976 - Order of St. John Investiture Ceremony At The Grand Priory Church - Clerkenwell; Over 130 members of the Order of St. John and the St. John Ambulshos |last=Limited |first=Alamy |website=Alamy |access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51558 |date=13 December 1988 |page=13986}}</ref> (28 June 1928&nbsp;\u2013 3 September 2010) was a British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]]. After his death, numerous allegations of [[child sexual abuse]] by Smith emerged (including many made during his lifetime), leading the police to believe that Smith was a [[Sex offender|serial sex offender]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20516533 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Former MP sexually abused boys, police say |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nSmith was first active in local politics as a Liberal in 1945 before switching to [[Labour Party (United Kingdom)|Labour]] in 1950; he served as a Labour councillor in [[Rochdale]] from 1950 and became mayor in 1966. He subsequently switched parties again and entered Parliament as a Liberal in 1972, winning his Rochdale seat on five further occasions. Smith was appointed the [[Liberal Chief Whip]] in June 1975 but later resigned on health grounds. In his later years as an MP, Smith opposed an [[SDP\u2013Liberal Alliance|alliance]] with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and did not stand for re-election in 1992, but remained loyal to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] upon the parties' merger. Throughout much of his career, he maintained a high profile in the media, and became a well-known public figure.\n\nIn later years, his public esteem was considerably marred by the allegation that he had been involved in a cover-up of a health risk at a local [[asbestos]] factory. In 2008, there were calls for Smith to be stripped of his [[knighthood]] after it was revealed that he had asked the asbestos company [[Turner & Newall]] to prepare a speech for him in 1981, in which he declared: \"the public at large are not at risk from asbestos\".<ref name=\"DanczukBaker2014\">{{cite book |author1=Simon Danczuk |author2=Matthew Baker |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRSuAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT128 |date=15 April 2014 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |isbn=978-1-84954-730-7 |page=128}}</ref> It was later revealed that Smith owned 1,300 shares in the company. In 2008, Smith said that 4,000 asbestos-related deaths a year in the UK was \"relatively low\".<ref name=\"Howker\">{{cite news |last=Howker |first=Ed |work=[[New Statesman]] |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/health/2008/08/asbestos-victims-company |title=Asbestos: The lies that killed |accessdate=15 May 2009 |date=28 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, following allegations of child abuse, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] formally admitted that Smith should have been charged with the sexual abuse of boys during his lifetime. [[Greater Manchester Police]] (GMP) said the boys \"were victims of physical and sexual abuse\" by Smith.<ref name=\"Dodd\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/cyril-smith-claims-decision-prosecute |title=Cyril Smith abuse claims: 'decision not to prosecute would not be made today' |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 November 2012 |last1=Dodd |first1=Vikram |last2=Syal |first2=Rajeev |location=London |publisher=Guardian News and Media}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20516533 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Former MP sexually abused boys, police say |publisher=BBC News |date=27 November 2012 |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> In November 2012, GMP Assistant Chief Constable Steve Heywood said there was \"overwhelming evidence\" that young boys were sexually and physically abused by Smith.<ref name=\"police1\">{{cite web |title=Statement regarding Sir Cyril Smith |url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/Content/WebsitePages/A22934C753EF3F0380257AC300607543?OpenDocument |publisher=Greater Manchester Police |accessdate=29 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203091905/http://www.gmp.police.uk/Content/WebsitePages/A22934C753EF3F0380257AC300607543?OpenDocument |archivedate=3 December 2012  }}</ref> In April 2014, it was reported that there had been 144 complaints against Smith from victims as young as eight, but attempts to prosecute him had always been blocked. Public authorities including [[Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|Rochdale Borough Council]], the police and intelligence services have been implicated in covering up Smith's crimes.<ref name=\"harrison1\">{{cite news |last=Harrison |first=Jody |title=Seven new child abuse claims against Cyril Smith |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/crime-courts/seven-new-child-abuse-claims-against-cyril-smith.23946227 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |newspaper=Sunday Herald |location=Glasgow |date=13 April 2014}}</ref> In 2015, it emerged that Smith had been arrested in the early 1980s in relation to these offences, but a high-level cover-up reportedly led to his being released within hours, the evidence destroyed and the investigating officers prevented from discussing the matter under the [[Official Secrets Act]].<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31908431 |title=Cyril Smith child abuse inquiry 'scrapped after his arrest'|publisher=BBC News |date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nSmith was born in Rochdale, [[Lancashire]], and described himself as \"illegitimate, deprived and poor.\"<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/politics-obituaries/7980251/Sir-Cyril-Smith.html |title=Sir Cyril Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref> Though he never knew the name of his father, he commented \"I suspect I know who he was.\"<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\"/> He lived with his mother, two illegitimate half-siblings, Eunice and Norman, and his grandmother in a [[Two-up two-down|one-up one-down cottage]] (now demolished) on Falinge Road. His mother, Eva Smith, worked in service to a local cotton mill\u2013owning family who lived at 8 Kilnerdyne Terrace.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977|p=18}}</ref>\n\nSmith was educated at [[Balderstone Technology College|Rochdale Grammar School for Boys]] and after leaving began work at Rochdale [[Inland Revenue]] Tax Office. In the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], aged 16, he gave a public speech in support of Liberal candidate Charles Harvey. Smith said he was given an ultimatum by his manager in the tax office to either choose the civil service or politics.\n\nHe left his job at the tax office and then worked as an office boy at Fothergill & Harvey's mill in [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]], northeast of Rochdale. The mill was owned by the Harveys, a notable Liberal family, but Smith claimed<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977|p=49}}</ref> the director Charles Harvey knew nothing of the job application by the young man who had lost his job for his public speech in favour of Harvey's Liberal candidature.<ref>''[[Rochdale Observer]]'' p17, 24 June 1996</ref>\n\nHe was a lifelong member of the [[Unitarianism|Rochdale Unitarian Church]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes flood in for Sir Cyril |url=http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/46608/tributes-flood-in-for-sir-cyril |accessdate=13 November 2016 |publisher=Rochdale Online |date=3 September 2010}}</ref> Contemporaries remembered him expressing, as a teenager, the desire to be both mayor and MP.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=letter to \"Lives Remembered\" |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2719326.ece |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=[[The Times]] |date=9 September 2010}}</ref> He served in many roles, including as Sunday School superintendent, trustee, and chair of the trustees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peel |first1=Gillian (Rev.) |title=SIR CYRIL SMITH MBE |url=http://www.nufonline.org.uk/NewNUF09/pdfs/NL392.pdf |accessdate=13 November 2016 |issue=392 |publisher=National Unitarian Fellowship |date=November\u2013December 2010}}</ref> His Unitarian faith intersected with his Liberal politics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenyon |first1=Neville |title=Letters: Sir Cyril Smith obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2010/sep/14/sir-cyril-smith-obituary-letters |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=14 September 2010}}</ref> Smith credited the church with \"helping develop his fiercely independent and anti-establishment streak\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Danczuk |first1=Simon |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Early career===\nSmith joined the Liberal Party in 1945 and was a member of the National Executive Committee of the [[National League of Young Liberals|Young Liberals]] in 1948 and 1949. From 1948 to 1950, he was Liberal agent in [[Stockport (UK Parliament constituency)|Stockport]], but after the poor general election results experienced by the Liberal Party [[1950 United Kingdom general election|in 1950]] and [[1951 United Kingdom general election|1951]] he was advised by the losing Liberal candidate for Stockport, Reg Hewitt, to join the Labour Party.\n\nIn 1952, Smith was elected a Labour Party councillor for the Falinge ward of Rochdale. By 1954, he was chairman of Rochdale Council's Establishment Committee. In 1963 he switched committee roles to be responsible for Estates which included overseeing residential and town centre development.\n\nHe was appointed the Labour Mayor of Rochdale in 1966, with his mother, Eva, acting as mayoress (she retained her job as a cleaner in [[Rochdale Town Hall]] whilst in the post). In her work as a cleaner at the town hall, she was banned from entering the police station \u2013 likewise based in the building \u2013 for she would search through its bins for information to help her son.{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=208}}\n\nSmith's mayoral duties were filmed for the BBC's ''[[Man Alive (BBC TV series)|Man Alive]]'' documentary series, in an episode titled \"Santa Claus for a Year\".{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=55}} In 1966 he was appointed chairman of the Education Committee overseeing the introduction of [[comprehensive education]] in the district. In the same year he was appointed Member of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]]. According to his autobiography,{{sfn|Smith|1977|p=107}} Smith was found guilty of an offence relating to public lotteries and bound over to keep the peace for 12 months.\n\nIn 1966, Smith resigned the Labour [[whip (politics)|whip]] when the party refused to vote for an increase in [[council house]] rents and sat with four other councillors as independents until 1970. His subsequent return to the Liberal Party, and his election as a Liberal MP, caused surprise after his role in opposing [[Ludovic Kennedy]], the Liberal candidate in the [[1958 Rochdale by-election]]. Controversy was sparked by Rochdale Liberals when the parliamentary candidate, Garth Pratt, was deselected to make way for Smith's return to the party.\n\nDuring the 1960s Smith was active on many Rochdale Council committees regarding youth activities. These included: Rochdale Youth Orchestra, Rochdale Youth Theatre Workshop, governorship of 29 Rochdale schools and chairmanship of the Youth Committee, Youth Employment Committee and the Education Committee.{{sfn|Smith|1977|p=101}}\n\n===Member of Parliament===\nHaving been Liberal candidate in [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] at the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]] when he took the party to second place, Smith won the seat at the [[1972 Rochdale by-election|1972 by-election]] with a large swing from Labour to the Liberals, and a majority of 5,171.\n\nHe was appointed as the party Chief Whip in June 1975, and faced pressure from the press in the wake of a scandal involving party leader [[Jeremy Thorpe]]. Smith was in hospital when Thorpe sacked him, just before himself being forced to resign.<ref name=\"Meadowcroft\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/sir-cyril-smith-obituary |title=Sir Cyril Smith obituary |work=The Guardian |date=3 September 2010 |last=Meadowcroft |first=Michael |location=London}}</ref> Speaking to [[Granada Television]] in 2003, [[David Steel]] reflected on events in the 1970s with the conclusion: \"Cyril was not an ideal Chief Whip because he did not handle a crisis well and had a tendency to say anything to a news camera.\"<ref>\"Nice One Cyril\" [[ITV Granada]]. Broadcast date 22 June 2003</ref> He was the only Liberal MP during his parliamentary career to oppose abortion and advocate the return of the death penalty.<ref name=\"TelegraphObit\"/><ref>Oliver Kamm [http://timesopinion.tumblr.com/post/35705574839/the-small-mind-of-sir-cyril-smith-paedophile \"The small mind of Sir Cyril Smith, paedophile\"], ''The Times'' (Opinion blog), 14 November 2012</ref> One of his constituents was jailed for 16 years for [[Murder of Lesley Molseed|the sexual murder of a child]], in what turned out to be a miscarriage of justice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McSmith |first1=Andy |title=Miscarriage of justice corrected as jury finds man guilty of murder |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/miscarriage-of-justice-corrected-as-jury-finds-man-guilty-of-murder-400089.html |accessdate=13 November 2016 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=13 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A terrible crime with two victims |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/a-terrible-crime-with-two-victims-1047375 |accessdate=13 November 2016 |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=13 August 2010}}</ref> The man's mother repeatedly approached Smith for help, but he declined to take the case on.<ref>''Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith''. \"Silent Voices #3\".</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Smith approached former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Prime Minister of the UK|Prime Minister]] [[Ted Heath]] to discuss forming a new centre party. In 1980, Smith described UK unemployment figures of two million jobless people as \"a disgrace\". Smith said: \"They represent a sick society, and are not acceptable to live with.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=McBain |first=Barclay |title=Smith attacks Government over jobless 'disgrace' |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AsRAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3053,2354670&dq=smith+attacks+government&hl=en |accessdate=14 July 2013 |newspaper=The Glasgow Herald |date=11 September 1980}}</ref> In 1981, Smith was involved in moves to create \"a party with a new image\" but, according to the ''[[Rochdale Observer]]'', at the foundation of the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in 1981 he warned Liberal Party colleagues to move with caution. Smith was quoted as being \"opposed to an alliance at any price\".<ref>''Rochdale Observer'', 24 June 1996</ref> He would later express the view that the Liberal Party would have been \"better off\" without being \"shackled to the SDP\".<ref name=\"menmedia\" /> After [[David Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]'s 1988 bill to reduce the time limit for abortions was talked out by MPs, he referred to other members as \"murderers in the womb\". The speaker of the House of Commons forced him to apologise for the comment.<ref name=\"Kamm2010\">{{cite news |url=http://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/oliver-kamm/35504/gross/ |title=Gross |work=The Times |location=London |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=1 February 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n===Asbestos===\nIn 2008 the ''[[New Statesman]]'' accused him of improper conduct in his connection with the company [[Turner & Newall]] (T&N), which was based in his constituency, and was once the world's largest manufacturer of materials using [[asbestos]].<ref name=\"Howker\"/> In the summer recess of 1981, Smith wrote to Sydney Marks, head of personnel at T&N, informing him that EEC regulations were coming up for debate in the next parliamentary session. A House of Commons speech he delivered was almost identical to one prepared for him by the company.<ref name=\"Howker\"/> \"The public at large are not at risk\" he said in his speech of a substance then long known as lethal if inhaled.<ref name=\"Howker\"/> A year later Smith revealed he owned 1,300 shares in the company.<ref name=\"Meadowcroft\"/> Interviewed in September 2008 by the BBC's local news programme, he responded to the claims he had helped cover up the dangers of asbestos as \"absolute rubbish\".<ref>[http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/21/spodden-valley/13616/sir-cyril-smith-defends-himself-on-bbc-news \"Sir Cyril Smith defends himself on BBC News\"], ''Rochdale News'', 4 September 2008. See also Alice McKeegan [http://menmedia.co.uk/rochdaleobserver/news/s/1065028_cyril_there_was_no_cover_up_on_asbestos \"Cyril: There was no cover up on asbestos\"], ''Manchester Evening News'', 2 September 2012</ref> After Smith's death, he was described by journalist [[Oliver Kamm]] in his blog in ''[[The Times]]'' as \"a corrupt, mendacious mountain of flesh\".<ref name=\"Kamm2010\"/>\n\nThe controversy led in November 2008 to a parliamentary [[early day motion]] calling for Smith to be stripped of the knighthood he had been granted in 1988.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/edm/2007-08/2470 EDM 2470], parliament.uk website, 11 November 2008</ref> [[Kevin Maguire (journalist)|Kevin Maguire]] of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' supported the motion.<ref>[http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/16086/national-newspaper-calls-for-sir-cyril-to-lose-knighthood \"National newspaper calls for Sir Cyril to lose knighthood\"], ''Rochdale Online'', 5 November 2008</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nAfter leaving Westminster and the death of his mother Eva in 1994, Smith was invited by a lifelong friend, the public relations manager at [[Cunard Line|Cunard]], to become a guest lecturer on the [[QE2]] cruise liner.<ref>''Lancashire Life'', June 1998</ref> He liked to spend his holidays at [[Lytham St Annes]], a seaside resort near Blackpool.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Chris |title=Sir Cyril Smith \u2013 A personal note from Rochdale Euro-MP Chris Davies |url=http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/46629/sir-cyril-smith-%E2%80%93-a-personal-note-from-rochdale-euromp-chris |accessdate=13 November 2016 |publisher=Rochdale Online |date=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006, Smith was taken to hospital after collapsing at his Rochdale home. He had been weakened by dehydration and low [[potassium]] levels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sir Cyril 'recovering' after fall |date=18 February 2006 |accessdate=20 November 2012 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/4727424.stm |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nSmith died of cancer in a Rochdale nursing home on 3 September 2010.<ref name=\"menmedia\">{{cite news |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1315976_former_rochdale_mp_sir_cyril_smith_dies_at_age_of_82 |title=Tributes to Sir Cyril Smith, a giant of politics |work=Manchester Evening News |publisher=M.E.N. Media |date=3 September 2010 |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> Smith had made detailed plans for his own funeral. It was held in the Great Hall of Rochdale Town Hall, and those who spoke included [[David Alton]], the MEP [[Chris Davies (Liberal Democrat politician)|Chris Davies]], and former MP [[Paul Rowen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rochdale says goodbye to Sir Cyril Smith|url=https://rochdalelibdems.org.uk/en/article/2010/0091439/rochdale-says-goodbye-to-sir-cyril-smith|website=Rochdale Liberal Democrats|accessdate=13 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114170953/https://rochdalelibdems.org.uk/en/article/2010/0091439/rochdale-says-goodbye-to-sir-cyril-smith|archivedate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Of all the many tributes, the then-current leader of Rochdale Council summed him up: \"He simply was politics for Rochdale.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sir Cyril Smith: Tributes pour in|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/sir-cyril-smith-tributes-pour-898296|accessdate=13 November 2016|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> The service was led by the minister of his local Unitarian church, of which he had been a lifelong member.<ref>[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/remembrance-service-for-sir-cyril-900673 Remembrance service for Sir Cyril] ''Manchester Evening News'' 8 October 2010</ref>\n\nHis younger brother Norman followed him into local politics, as councillor, mayor, and president of the local Liberal Democrat chapter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norman Smith MBE named as new Lib Dem President|url=http://rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news/49734/norman-smith-mbe-named-as-new-lib-dem-president|accessdate=13 November 2016|publisher=Rochdale Online|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Popular image==\nSmith's large size and capacity for blunt speaking and popular touch made him one of the most recognisable British politicians of the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"menmedia\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11180264 BBC News, \"Former Liberal Democrat MP Cyril Smith dies\", 3 September 2010]. Retrieved 17 March 2015</ref> His nickname, \"Big Cyril\", was the title of his autobiography.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1977}}</ref> He made many popular television appearances: he sang \"She's a Lassie from Lancashire\" on his friend [[Jimmy Savile]]'s early-1970s TV show ''Clunk Click'',<ref>{{cite news |title='Paedophiles' Cyril Smith & Jimmy Savile Were Friends For 40 Years |last=Nelson |first=Sara C |work=Huffington Post |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/29/paedophiles-cyril-smith-jimmy-savile-friends-_n_2210121.html |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=30 November 2012}}</ref> appeared in an advert for a \"greatest hits\" album by 1980s pop group [[Bananarama]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16941969 |title=Lembit Opik stars in unsigned band's music video |publisher=BBC News |date=8 February 2012 |accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> and sang a duet with [[Don Estelle]] in a 1999 recording of the [[Laurel and Hardy]] song \"[[The Trail of the Lonesome Pine (song)|The Trail of the Lonesome Pine]]\".<ref name=\"obituary\">Don Estelle obituary. ''The Independent'', 4 August 2003 {{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref> Like several other prominent British MPs in the 1980s, he was regularly parodied in the satirical television show ''[[Spitting Image]]''.{{sfn|Danczuk|Baker|2014|p=11}}\n\nHe is believed to have been the heaviest British MP ever: at 6'2\" (188&nbsp;cm) he was reported to weigh 29 [[stone (Imperial mass)|stone]] 12 pounds, about 190 kilogrammes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochdale-makes-its-mark-at-last-to-the-regret-of-mr-brown-1958907.html |title=Rochdale makes its mark at last, to the regret of Mr Brown |date=30 April 2010 |work=The Independent |accessdate=5 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref> A common joke on the size of the Parliamentary Liberal Party in the early 1970s was that only one taxi would be needed to transport the entire party; after Smith's election, the party could fill two taxis.<ref>BBC Nationwide 1972</ref>\n\nA lifelong bachelor, Smith told ''[[You (British magazine)|You]]'' magazine: \"I haven't had a lot of time for courting women&nbsp;... I've tended to be married to politics\".<ref name=\"menmedia\" /><ref>''You'' magazine: 9 May 1993</ref> It was later alleged that he sexually assaulted adolescent boys.<ref name=elm/> He was a friend of the mother of broadcasters [[Andy Kershaw|Andy]] and [[Liz Kershaw]]; she described him as dependent on [[Diazepam|Valium]], but he denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beattie |first1=Jason |title=Sir Cyril Smith dies aged 82 - but was there a darker side to the former MP? |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/sir-cyril-smith-dies-aged-245375 |accessdate=13 November 2016 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of child sexual abuse==\n\n===Early allegations===\nIn May 1979, a local [[underground magazine]], the ''Rochdale Alternative Press'', alleged that in the 1960s Smith had spanked and sexually abused teenage boys in a hostel he co-founded. The matter was investigated by the police but Smith was not prosecuted. The story was repeated in the same month by the satirical magazine ''[[Private Eye]]''.<ref>''Private Eye'' No. 454 (11 May 1979), p. 3.</ref> Smith never publicly denied the accusations of abuse, nor did he ever take legal action, but after his death the allegations were denied by his family.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1328218_cyrils_family_in_fury_at_cowardly_article |title=Cyril's family in fury at 'cowardly' article |work=Manchester Evening News |date=17 September 2010 |last=Storey |first=Katie |publisher=M.E.N. Media}}</ref><ref>[http://mooredge.com/mooredgenews.html \"Does Rochdale really want a LibDem MP??\"]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>Private Eye, No.1271. September 2010</ref> The Press Office of the leader of the Liberal Party, [[David Steel]] commented, \"All he seems to have done is spanked a few bare bottoms\".<ref>''Private Eye'' No. 1329 (14 December 2012), p. 10.</ref>\n\n===2012===\nIn November 2012, speaking in the House of Commons, [[Simon Danczuk]],<ref name = \"Danczuk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2012-11-13a.208.0&s |title=House of Commons, 13 November 2012, \"Backbench Business \u2014 Child Sexual Exploitation\", Simon Danczuk, 4.29pm |work=TheyWorkForYou.com, UK Parliament |date=13 November 2012}}</ref> the Labour [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for Rochdale, Smith's old seat, called for an inquiry into the alleged abuse.<ref name = \"Danczuk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20303606 |title=Rochdale MP calls for Cyril Smith 'indecent assault' inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Rossendale]] councillor Alan Neal said that at the age of 11 in 1964, during Smith's membership of the Labour Party, he was beaten by Smith at a hostel for boys.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20337495 |title=Councillor makes MP abuse claim |date=15 November 2012 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> Neal said: \"I'm speaking now because someone has taken a right decision to raise this issue with the authorities\". He added that he told police about the incident in 1968 when he left the school but on raising it \"everyone made the same comment that the person in question was a very important, powerful man\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20337495 |title=Councillor accuses Sir Cyril Smith of physical abuse |publisher=BBC News |date=15 November 2012 |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref> Neal said that he lost two front teeth and needed stitches to a head wound after Smith assaulted him for refusing to eat a potted meat sandwich.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former East Lancs mayor backs call for Sir Cyril Smith child abuse inquiry |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/11150749.Former_East_Lancs_mayor_backs_call_for_Sir_Cyril_Smith_child_abuse_inquiry/ |accessdate=26 April 2014 |newspaper=Lancashire Telegraph |date=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnother alleged victim of abuse by Smith waived his right to anonymity in November 2012 to claim that Smith smacked him and stroked his buttocks when he was a teenager at a Rochdale care home in the 1960s. Barry Fitton said he was spanked \"very, very hard\" by Smith and that he was left in tears by the alleged incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20329227 |title=Sir Cyril Smith: Accuser 'left in tears' after 'abuse' |publisher=BBC News |date=14 November 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2012, [[Greater Manchester Police]] announced it would investigate allegations that Smith had sexually abused boys at a hostel in Rochdale after 1974, and [[Lancashire Police]] would investigate claims dating from before 1974. The police said it would look at whether investigations had taken place into Smith during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/policy-inquiry-launched-in-sir-cyril-smith-abuse-allegations |title=Policy inquiry launched in Sir Cyril Smith abuse allegations |work=Channel 4 News |date=21 November 2012 |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 2012, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] said that Smith should have been charged with crimes of abuse more than 40 years earlier. In a statement, Greater Manchester Police said the boys \"were victims of physical and sexual abuse\" by the ex-Rochdale MP. Smith was never charged although investigations were undertaken in 1970, 1998, and 1999. The method of assessing the probability of a conviction has changed since 1970, and the decision not to charge Smith then necessitated the outcome of the 1998 investigation. Following the sexual abuse allegations, Rochdale Council removed a [[blue plaque]] to Smith from the town hall.<ref name=\"Dodd\" /><ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nGreater Manchester Police Assistant Chief Constable Steve Heywood said: \"Although Smith cannot be charged or convicted posthumously, from the overwhelming evidence we have it is right and proper we should publicly recognise that young boys were sexually and physically abused\".<ref name=\"police1\"/>\n\nOn 28 November 2012, an alleged victim of sexual abuse by Smith waived his right to anonymity in a television interview with [[Sky News]] to say that he was sexually abused by Smith at a council-run residential special school. Chris Marshall broke down in tears during his interview when describing the sexual abuse he said took place at Knowl View school in Rochdale in the early 1980s. He said that as a nine-year-old boy he was taken to a room and made to perform oral sex on Smith and one other man. Smith was a governor at the school and allegedly had his own set of keys. Liberal Democrat leader [[Nick Clegg]] said: \"I am deeply shocked and horrified by these terrible allegations and my thoughts are with the victims who had the courage to speak out\".<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Mike |title=Cyril Smith: Former MP 'Abused Me As A Child' |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1017895/cyril-smith-former-mp-abused-me-as-a-child |accessdate=14 July 2013 |publisher=Sky News |date=28 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Tony Robinson, a former [[Special Branch]] officer with Lancashire Police in the 1970s, said that a dossier of sexual abuse allegations against Smith which police claimed was \"lost\" was actually seized by [[MI5]]. Robinson said that he was asked by MI5 to send to London a police dossier that had been kept in a safe in his office which he said was \"thick\" with allegations from boys claiming they had been abused by Smith.<ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |title=Sir Cyril Smith sex abuse dossier seized by MI5 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/9678697/Sir-Cyril-Smith-sex-abuse-dossier-seized-by-MI5.html |accessdate=29 March 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Rochdale MP Simon Danczuk alleged that Smith raped some of his victims. Danczuk said: \"There is no doubt that Cyril Smith seriously sexually abused young boys: why the CPS didn't prosecute more recently is puzzling\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Cyril Smith 'raped some of his victims', MP says |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-20568253 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing claims by MP [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] of \"a powerful paedophile network linked to Parliament and No 10\", it was reported that Scotland Yard detectives investigating [[Elm Guest House claims and controversy|allegations of child abuse at the Elm Guest House]] were looking into allegations that senior politicians abused children in the 1980s and escaped justice.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/scotland-yard-investigating-allegations-senior-politicians-abused-children-in-the-1980s-and-used-connections-to-escape-justice-8411989.html |author=Hickman, Martin |title=Scotland Yard investigating allegations senior politicians abused children in the 1980s and used 'connections' to escape justice |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=12 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nIn January 2013, ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' reported that police were investigating claims that Smith sexually abused boys at the London guest house.<ref>{{cite news |first1=James |last1=Hanning |first2=Paul |last2=Cahalan |title=Cyril Smith named in Barnes abuse case |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/cyril-smith-named-in-barnes-abuse-case-8468370.html |accessdate=24 March 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent on Sunday]] |location=London |date=27 January 2013}}</ref> A spokesman for the Metropolitan Police later said: \"We can confirm Cyril Smith visited the premises.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Sir Cyril Smith 'visited alleged sex abuse guest house' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-24074818 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 September 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> A 16-year-old boy was allegedly sexually abused by Smith at Elm Guest House.<ref name=elm>{{cite news |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |title='Influential' politician visited guest house at centre of child sex investigation |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10775360/Influential-politician-visited-guest-house-at-centre-of-child-sex-investigation.html |accessdate=9 July 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 April 2014}}</ref> MP [[Simon Danczuk]] said he was convinced that there was a \"network of paedophiles\" operating in the House of Commons who helped to protect Smith.<ref name=elm/>\n\nIn September 2013, a [[Channel 4]] ''[[Dispatches (TV programme)|Dispatches]]'' programme \"The Paedophile MP: How Cyril Smith Got Away With It\" quoted the Crown Prosecution Service as claiming that they had not prosecuted Smith for crimes of abuse because he had been given an assurance in 1970 that he would not be prosecuted, and that prevented them from subsequently reopening the investigation under the law at the time. Political journalist [[Francis Wheen]] said that he found this explanation incomprehensible.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dispatches: Episode Guide |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/dispatches/episode-guide |work=Channel 4.com |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nDanczuk, with researcher and campaigner Matthew Baker, published ''Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith'', an expos\u00e9 of the child abuse committed by Smith. Danczuk alleged that Smith was part of a high-level paedophile ring and that Smith had used his influence to escape prosecution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bitebackpublishing.com/books/smile-for-the-camera-hardback |title=Smile for the Camera |publisher=Biteback publishing |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Paedophile ring protected Sir Cyril Smith, MP claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27047442 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> Danczuk said: \"Once you looked beyond the jolly clown playing for the camera, there was a sickening, dark heart. This wasn't just about abuse, it was about power - and a cover-up that reached from Rochdale all the way to the very top of the Establishment.\"<ref name=\"harrison1\"/> Danczuk said that in the 1980s police discovered child pornography belonging to Smith, but he escaped justice.<ref name=Danczuk1>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=MP defends book on Cyril Smith |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/book-describes--ex-rochdale-mp-6990663 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=14 May 2014 |date=15 April 2014}}</ref> Danczuk described Smith as \"a predatory paedophile and a prolific offender who would target the most vulnerable boys.\" He said: \"A lot of manpower went into investigating Smith over the years, but the only thing he was ever convicted for was mis-selling a lottery ticket.\"<ref name=Danczuk1/>\n\nIn 2014, former Liberal leader Sir [[David Steel]] said he had confronted Smith about his \"unusual\" behaviour with boys at a hostel in Rochdale. Following allegations published in 1979, Steel said that Smith confessed to spanking boys and conducting intimate \"medical examinations\" on them but was allowed to remain as a Liberal MP. Steel said: \"I asked Cyril Smith about it. I was half expecting him to say it was all wrong, and I would have been urging him to sue to save his reputation. To my surprise he said the report was correct.\" Steel said that Smith had a supervisory role in institutions in Rochdale where he was involved in [[corporal punishment]]. Steel said of the abuse allegations: \"They had been investigated by the police, as ''Private Eye'' stated, and no action had been taken on them. So there was nothing more I could do.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Swinford |first=Steven |title=Cyril Smith admitted spanking and touching boys, but I let him stay, says Lord Steel |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/10796546/Cyril-Smith-admitted-spanking-and-touching-boys-but-I-let-him-stay-says-Lord-Steel.html |accessdate=11 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, following reports that there had been 144 complaints against Smith and that attempts to prosecute him had always been blocked,<ref name=\"harrison1\"/> the President of the Liberal Democrats, [[Tim Farron]], said that his party needed to answer \"serious questions\" about who knew that Smith had faced allegations of sexual assault.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lib Dems face 'questions' over Cyril Smith abuse claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27166442 |publisher=BBC News |date=26 April 2014}}</ref> However, Liberal Democrat leader [[Nick Clegg]] refused to hold an inquiry into what he called the \"repugnant\" actions of Smith. Clegg said: \"My party, the Liberal Democrats, did not know about these actions.\" Clegg stated that the child abuse allegations were a matter for the police.<ref>{{cite news |last=Graham |first=Georgia |title=Nick Clegg refuses to hold inquiry into Cyril Smith child abuse allegations |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nick-clegg/10765504/Nick-Clegg-refuses-to-hold-inquiry-into-Cyril-Smith-child-abuse-allegations.html |accessdate=4 May 2014 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, it was alleged that Smith had molested an 11-year-old boy at the [[National Liberal Club]] in London in 1978. Smith allegedly insisted that the boy remove his underpants before attempting to fondle him. A spokesman for the Liberal Democrats said: \"Cyril Smith's acts were vile and repugnant and we have nothing but sympathy for those whose lives he ruined.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Sammon |first=Gerry |title=Cyril Smith molested 11-year-old boy - claim |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/allegation-disgraced-former-rochdale-mp-7192245 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=30 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Detective Chief Superintendent Russ Jackson of Greater Manchester Police admitted the force's previous investigations into abuse linked to Smith at Rochdale Knowl View residential school \"fell well short\" of what would be expected today.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Jennifer |title=Police admit '90s probe into Knowl View abuse scandal 'fell well short' of today's standards |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/knowl-view-abuse-scandal-investigation-7259254 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=12 June 2014}}</ref> Allegations were made that a paedophile ring had been operating for decades in the town of Rochdale and that men from as far away as [[Sheffield]] were travelling to Rochdale to have sex with Knowl View boys aged between eight and thirteen.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thomas |first=Ed |title=Knowl View: Rochdale Council 'misled' police amid school abuse claims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-27427952 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 June 2014}}</ref> Greater Manchester Police said there were 21 suspects, 14 of whom it had identified, including Smith.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cyril Smith sex abuse allegations: Seven men come forward |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-27427952 |accessdate=22 June 2014 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In July 2014, Rochdale council's inquiry into child abuse linked to Smith at Knowl View residential school was halted at the request of police. Greater Manchester Police asked the authority to suspend their inquiry while detectives investigated claims of an institutional cover-up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Jennifer |title=Home Office could be called in to investigate 'child abuse cover-up' at Cyril Smith school |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/home-office-knowl-view-probe-7386381 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, it was reported that Smith had put pressure on the [[BBC]] in 1976, by asking the corporation not to investigate the \"private lives of certain MPs\". According to letters in the [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|National Archives]], Smith wrote to BBC Director-General [[Charles Curran (broadcaster)|Sir Charles Curran]] in September 1976 saying he was \"deeply concerned about the investigative activities of the BBC\", especially relating to \"the private lives of certain MPs\". Former children's minister [[Tim Loughton]] described Smith's letters as \"bully-boy tactics\". Loughton said: \"It was an abuse of position that somebody as an MP was saying, 'You shouldn't look at us, we're above the law.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Bateman |first=Tom |title=Cyril Smith 'put pressure on BBC' over investigating MPs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28093405 |accessdate=9 July 2014 |publisher=BBC News |date=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nA report released by the Crown Prosecution Service in July 2014 showed that in 1970 a police detective investigating Smith presented evidence to his superior of Smith's abuse of young boys at a care home in Rochdale, but no action was taken.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Syal |first1=Rajeev |title=Cyril Smith: 'evidence of sex abuse' was overruled CPS report shows |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/16/cyril-smith-sex-abuse-cps-1970-report-lancashire-dpp |accessdate=17 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nIn March 2015, [[Cabinet Office]] papers were released confirming that Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] was made aware of allegations against Smith before he was knighted in 1988.<ref>{{cite news |title=Margaret Thatcher 'told of Cyril Smith abuse claims' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31789827 |accessdate=10 March 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=8 March 2015}}</ref> Shortly after, a BBC investigation on ''[[Newsnight]]'' revealed that Smith had been arrested in the early 1980s in relation to his participation in a paedophile ring, but a high-level cover-up reportedly led to him being released within hours, the evidence destroyed and the investigating officers prevented from discussing the matter under the [[Official Secrets Act]].<ref name=\"BBC News\"/> [[Theresa May]], the Home Secretary, called for immunity for whistle-blowers in the case.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/mar/17/home-secretary-theresa-may-cyril-smith-cover-up-claims-shocking-prosecutions |title=Home secretary: Cyril Smith cover-up claims 'could lead to prosecutions' |work=The Guardian |accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Reports also emerged of Smith's arrest by [[Northamptonshire Police]], where he was again released in mysterious circumstances.<ref>{{cite news |title='Cyril Smith M1 arrest to be probed by Northamptonshire Police' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-31964255 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a retired police officer said that he was threatened with the [[Official Secrets Act]] after he found Smith in the home of a known sex offender, with two drunk teenage boys, and a police sergeant in civilian clothes. The retired officer said that he was summoned to a meeting with a senior officer at Stockport Police Station and told \"in no uncertain terms\" not to say anything about it. The alleged incident took place in 1988 at a house in Stockport after a complaint that the occupier had been committing a lewd act in his window in front of a newspaper boy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keeling |first=Neal |title=Former officers asked to help with investigation into the alleged cover up of child sex abuse linked to Cyril Smith |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/police-chief-asks-ex-cops-help-8896730 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn October 2017 the [[Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse]] (IICSA) was told that [[MI5]] had been made aware that prosecutors lied to the press over the existence of a child abuse file on Smith. Detectives had said the \"sordid\" claims about the late MP's alleged abuse of young boys in 1970 \"stood up\". The enquiry heard how the investigation into Smith had \"illuminated\" wider abuse suffered by the boys. In 1988, when Smith was made a knight, then Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] had probably been informed of his chequered past. The hearings focused on alleged offences at Cambridge House hostel and the Knowl View residential school in Rochdale, where Smith was a governor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41547471 |title=MI5 'told of Cyril Smith abuse case lie' |date=9 October 2017 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Cyril Smith was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in 1966.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* He was invested as a Serving Brother of the [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|Order of St John]] in 1976.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/bright-knight-was-man-of-honours-898293 |title=Bright knight was man of honours |first=Manchester Evening |last=News |date=7 September 2010 |publisher= |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He served as [[Pro-vice-chancellor|Deputy Pro Chancellor]] of [[Lancaster University]] from 1978-1985.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scan.lusu.co.uk/index.php/2014/06/05/one-alumnus-that-should-not-have-kept-in-touch/ |title=One alumnus that should not have kept in touch |first=Daniel |last=Snape |date=5 June 2014 |publisher= |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* He was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in 1988, allowing him to be known as '''Sir Cyril Smith'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/cyril-smith-liberal-politics|title=Cyril Smith dies, 82 |first=Martin |last=Wainwright |date=3 September 2010 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He was appointed a [[Deputy lieutenant]] of [[Greater Manchester]] in 1991, allowing him the [[List of post-nominal letters (United Kingdom)|Post Nominal Letters]] \"DL\" for Life. \n* He was awarded the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Rochdale]] in November 1992. After a series of allegations of child sexual abuse, over a span of 30 years, came to light following his death, he was posthumously stripped of this honour by a unanimous vote of [[Rochdale Borough Council]] on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/123143/cyril-smith-stripped-of-the-freedom-of-borough |title=Cyril Smith stripped of the freedom of borough |website=www.rochdaleonline.co.uk |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* He was awarded the [[Honorary degree]] of [[Doctor of Laws]] by Lancaster University in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/about-us/ourpeople/honorary-degrees/#nineties |title=Honorary Graduates - Lancaster University |first=Lancaster |last=University |website=www.lancaster.ac.uk |accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|Greater Manchester|Politics|United Kingdom|Liberalism|Law}}\n* [[Westminster paedophile dossier]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Cyril |title=Big Cyril: Autobiography |year=1977 |publisher= |isbn=0-491-02261-1 |ref=harv}}\n* ''Reflections from Rochdale: As I Saw it and as I See it'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-85187-340-6}}. A later slimmer autobiographical work.\n* \"Cyril Smith\", entry by Tim Farron in Brack et al. (eds.) ''Dictionary of Liberal Biography'' (Politico's, 1998)\n* {{cite book |title=Smile for the Camera: The Double Life of Cyril Smith |year=2014 |first=Simon |last=Danczuk |authorlink=Simon Danczuk |first2=Matthew |last2=Baker |publisher=Biteback |isbn=978-1-84954-644-7 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs|mr-cyril-smith|Cyril Smith}}\n* [http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/content_objectid=13671488_method=full_siteid=50061_headline=-Sir-Cyril-in-fight-against-assembly-name_page.html Sir Cyril in fight against assembly]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/03/sir-cyril-smith-obituary Obituary in ''[[The Guardian]]'']\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-cyril-smith-idiosyncratic-and-largerthanlife-liberal-politician-who-never-shied-away-from-falling-out-with-his-own-party-2070138.html Obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'']\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/politics-obituaries/7980251/Sir-Cyril-Smith.html Obituary in ''The Telegraph'']\n* [http://www.rochdaleonline.co.uk/news-features/2/news-headlines/46629/sir-cyril-smith-%E2%80%93-a-personal-note-from-rochdale-euromp-chris Tribute in ''Rochdale Online''] by Chris Davies MEP\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par| uk}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Jack McCann]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale]] |years=[[1972 Rochdale by-election|1972]]\u2013[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Liz Lynne]] }}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[David Steel]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Liberal Chief Whip]] | years= 1976\u201377 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Alan Beith]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Child sexual abuse in the UK|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Cyril}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in England]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse cover-ups]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Rochdale]]\n[[Category:People from Rochdale]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Rochdale]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1978-1985 \u2192 1978\u20131985", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyril_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Barnard, Bishop & Barnards", "text_new": "{{in use}}\n{{under construction}}\n{{italics title}}\n[[File:Barnard-Bishop-and-Barnards medallion.jpg|thumb|<center>Signature medallion of the firm - a visual pun on the 4 partners' names starting with a 'B']]\n[[File:Charles Barnard02a.jpg|thumb|<center>Charles Barnard]]\n[[File:Sandringham, The Norwich Gates (geograph 4611332).jpg|thumb|<center>The Norwich Gates at [[Sandringham House]] constructed by Barnard, Bishop & Barnards]]\n'''''Barnard, Bishop & Barnards''''' was initially an ironmongery started by Charles Barnard (1804-1871) on 9 November 1826 in premises near [[Norwich Market]]. By 1840 his retail business had expanded and included iron foundry workshops in Pottergate, producing ironwork for domestic and agricultural purposes. Charles Barnard developed, but did not patent,  a technique for weaving wire into black japanned netting and fencing. The original loom may be seen at the [[Norwich#Museums|Bridewell Museum]] in Norwich. Fencing was in great demand in Australia to control the country's [[Rabbit plagues in Australia|rabbit problem]] and ensured a fortune for Barnard.\n \nIn 1846 John Bishop, from [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire|St. Ives]], joined the firm as a partner, and the flourishing business forced a move to a site bounded by St. George's, Colegate, and Calvert Streets. <ref>http://www.orangesmile.com/common/img_city_maps/norwich-map-0.jpg</ref> In 1859 Charles' two eldest sons also became partners leading to the firm's new name Barnard, Bishop & Barnards, and the adoption of its signature medallion of four bees. In 1861 Charles Barnard was recorded as proprietor of the works, employing 105 workmen, 47 boys, 7 clerks and 4 shopmen. <ref>http://www.airgale.com.au/bishop/d7.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{in use}}\n{{under construction}}\n{{italics title}}\n[[File:Barnard-Bishop-and-Barnards medallion.jpg|thumb|<center>Signature medallion of the firm - a visual pun on the 4 partners' names starting with a 'B']]\n[[File:Charles Barnard02a.jpg|thumb|<center>Charles Barnard]]\n[[File:Sandringham, The Norwich Gates (geograph 4611332).jpg|thumb|<center>The Norwich Gates at [[Sandringham House]] constructed by Barnard, Bishop & Barnards]]\n'''''Barnard, Bishop & Barnards''''' was initially an ironmongery started by Charles Barnard (1804-1871) on 9 November 1826 in premises near [[Norwich Market]]. By 1840 his retail business had expanded and included iron foundry workshops in Pottergate, producing ironwork for domestic and agricultural purposes. Charles Barnard developed, but did not patent,  a technique for weaving wire into black japanned netting and fencing. The original loom may be seen at the [[Norwich#Museums|Bridewell Museum]] in Norwich. Fencing was in great demand in Australia to control the country's [[Rabbit plagues in Australia|rabbit problem]] and ensured a fortune for Barnard.\n \nIn 1846 John Bishop, from [[St. Ives]], joined the firm as a partner, and the flourishing business forced a move to a site bounded by St. George's, Colegate, and Calvert Streets. <ref>http://www.orangesmile.com/common/img_city_maps/norwich-map-0.jpg</ref> In 1859 Charles' two eldest sons also became partners leading to the firm's new name Barnard, Bishop & Barnards, and the adoption of its signature medallion of four bees. In 1861 Charles Barnard was recorded as proprietor of the works, employing 105 workmen, 47 boys, 7 clerks and 4 shopmen. <ref>http://www.airgale.com.au/bishop/d7.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:St. Ives\u2192St Ives, Cambridgeshire", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barnard,_Bishop_%26_Barnards"}
